<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Official Barred from IMF Annual Meeting: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- West African diplomats in
Freetown said today that the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
has barred Joe Amara Bangali, Sierra Leone's Secretary of State
for Finance, from attending its current joint annual meeting in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
One diplomat told Xinhua that a letter was sent to Bangali who
was appointed by the military regime in Sierra Leone in June by
the IMF secretariat, stating that "only persons representing
governments that have international recognition and support are
eligible to attend the (Hong Kong) meeting."
</P>
<P>
"I am surprised over this ugly development," Bangali told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"When the (military) government came to power, and I took
office as Secretary of State for Finance, I informed the IMF
secretariat about my appointment, and that of Christian Kargbo,
governor of the Central Bank, and Simon Carew, Financial
Secretary, so they cannot say they were not aware."
</P>
<P>
According to Bangali, the IMF secretariat informed him about
the Hong Kong meeting and extended an invitation for him to
attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I think the fund's judgement should not be influenced by the
nature of the political regime of a country nor should it
interfere in the domestic or foreign politics of member states,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been looking forward to participating in the meeting
and deriving all the benefits due from such participation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The military government of Major Johnny Paul Koroma said after
the May 25 coup that it will continue "strict budgetary
expenditure and the structural adjustment program (SAP)" which
the IMF has instituted under the ousted civilian government but
the IMF has suspended all programm since last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
