<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Create Scholarship Fund for Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien has revealed that his government will set up a massive
scholarship fund for needy and high-achieving students.
</P>
<P>
The scholarship fund is expected to receive at least one
billion dollars (720 million USD) in seed money from the federal
government, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The fund, which will begin operating in 2000, will be designed
to provide thousands of university or college scholarships to
low-and moderate-income Canadians.
</P>
<P>
An endowment of this size would result in a 50-million to 70
million-dollar pool of cash on which to draw each year, a fund
that Chretien said would stand as his government's most
significant project to mark the millennium.
</P>
<P>
"On a very personal level, I hope (the fund) will be able to
do, in a different era, for many, many thousands of young
Canadians what my parents were able to do for me and my brothers
and sisters," Chretien said while making the announcement in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be "another dividend" of the elimination of the
federal deficit, and details will be made public later this year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative was denounced by Brad Lavigne, national
chairman of the Canadian Federation of Students.
</P>
<P>
Even with the availability of a few thousand scholarships, it
will only help "a small percentage of students with access to
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The solution is a national system of grants, not a merit-based
scholarship," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the move was welcomed by William Leggett, president of
Queen's University.
</P>
<P>
The announcement "is a very welcome move" because it represents
an attack on student debt loads, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's an important initiative. I hope that this leadership will
be followed by the provinces," Leggett added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
