<HEADLINE> UK World Trade Gap Narrows to 450m Pounds in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain's world trade deficit
for July narrowed down to 450 million pounds (725 million US
dollars), compared with a deficit of 950 million pounds (1.5
billion US dollars) in June, according to official figures
released today.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said that exports rose
by 4.2 percent in July while imports were 0.7 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
The figures were lower than City economists' prediction of a
deficit of around 500 million pounds (805 million US dollars), and
the ONS said that much of the improvement was due to a one-off
sale of a 400 million pounds (644 million US dollars) oil platform
to Norway.
</P>
<P>
Another reason was that there was little sign that sterling's
appreciation was hurting exports so far.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ONS also announced today that Britain's August
trade deficit with countries outside the European Union (EU)
swelled to 359 million pounds (578 million US dollars), compared
with a revised figure for July of just 62 million pounds (99.8
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of exports to non-EU countries fell 7.7 percent, while
imports dropped 3.4 percent, said the ONS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
