<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US of Obstructing Oil-for-Food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today accused the United
State for obstructing the completion of the first six-month stage
of the oil-for-food deal starting last December.
</P>
<P>
Some of these contracts which provide humanitarian goods to
sanctions-hit Iraq still have not been approved by the
U.N. Security Council Sanctions Committee due to U.S. hindrance,
said Iraqi Minister of Culture and Information Hamam Abdul-Khalek
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy food and medicine badly needed
for the Iraqi people who are suffering the sanctions imposed
following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, which has been extended for another six months,
each contract must be approved unanimously by all the sanction
committee members. The U.S. has alleged that Iraq could use some
of the imports for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
Citing one example of U.S. troublemaking, Khalek said a
contract for the purchase of 100 first-aid vehicles is still being
suspended.
</P>
<P>
He called Washington to put an end to such practices and not to
repeat them during the second stage of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
