<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges U.N. Members to Increase Aid to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of
the United Nations Kofi Annan today urged U.N. member states to do
all in their power to increase official development assistance to
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Ministerial Meeting of the U.N. Security Council
on Africa here, Annan said "the best way of ensuring peace and
security in Africa is to promote sustainable development."
</P>
<P>
"Releasing funds for development and supporting Africa are
important aims of my reform proposals," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He said external financing will continue to be of vital
importance for Africa besides the latter's mobilization of
internal resources.
</P>
<P>
He said a successful strategy should combine poverty
eradication with growth in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"To alleviate poverty in the short run and eradicate absolute
poverty, development assistance should be directed to poor rural
areas," he went on.
</P>
<P>
He also called for more action to relieve African countries of
their heavy debt service burden.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. will continue to work closely with the
Organization for African Unity and other regional organizations in
African peace-keeping.
</P>
<P>
International community should promise a mature relationship
with Africa, offering the prospects of targeted assistance and
support "based on common goals and shared analysis," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
