<HEADLINE> US Orders for Durable Goods Surge in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
for durable goods increased strongly in August resulting from a
record surge in demand for electrical equipment, U.S. Commerce
Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods -- items expected to last more than
three years -- rose by 2.7 percent to a record seasonally adjusted
186.6 billion dollars last month, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Much of the gain came from a 28.4 percent jump in electronic
and other electrical equipment, the largest increase on record
since the government began keeping track in 1958.
</P>
<P>
Excluding electronic orders, durable goods orders declined by
1.7 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Orders for transportation equipment, the only other category to
show substantial strength, gained by 5.2 percent as a large
increase for aircraft offset declines in other areas.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of durable goods, a measure of current production,
decreased by 1.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted 181.3 billion
dollars, the first drop in three months.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the big gain in orders and the decrease in
shipments, the backlog of unfilled orders rose 1.1 percent to a
seasonally adjusted 501.1 billion dollars, the third gain in four
months.
</P>
<P>
A rising backlog can signal production bottlenecks ahead but
some analysts said that the backlog increase was the result of a
temporary decline in shipments caused by the United Parcel Service
strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
