<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Pushes Reform Deal to Foreign Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan pushed his reform package at the
meeting of the foreign ministers of the Non-Aligned Movement here
today.
</P>
<P>
"A reformed United Nations will be a more relevant United
Nations in the eyes of the world," he told the ministers, adding
that it will restore the General Assembly to its proper role as
the democratic, universal expression of global demands.
</P>
<P>
He called the General Assembly which is holding its 52nd
session the "Reform Assembly", to show his will for reform.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged the member states to consider the reforms in an
integrated manner and as a package. He said that his reform
package should be dealt with and decided upon "as early as
possible."
</P>
<P>
He said that a reformed United Nations will tackle more
effectively the ills no one nation can defeat on its own: the
degradation of the environment; the trade in arms and illegal
drugs and transnational crime; and the plague of disease and
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
He added that a reformed United Nations will also bring back
into those countries which "have sometimes distanced themselves
from our collective efforts," to create a United Nations that is
truly united in pursuing these vital endeavors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
