<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT September 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
London -- Britain's press watchdog the Press Complaints
Commission (PCC) Thursday unveiled a series of new tough privacy
guidelines for the newspaper industry in the wake of the death of
Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines were drawn up as part of an urgent review of the
industry's Code of Practice, which began on September 1 just one
day after the death of Diana in a car accident, allegedly caused
by chasing photographers known as Paparazzi. (UK-Press-Privacy)
</P>
<P>
- - --
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French President Jacques Chirac left here Thursday on
a three-day state visit to Russia, said the Elysee Presidential
Palace.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will hold talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin
this afternoon and will make two speeches in Moscow and
Saint-Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
This is Chirac's second visit to Russia this year. He paid a
brief visit to Moscow in early February during which he discussed
with Yeltsin the signing of a charter on bilateral relations
between Russia and NATO. (France-Chirac-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- Visiting Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said
Thursday that the recent visit by Chinese Premier Li Peng to
Kazakhstan has raised the political and economic ties between the
two countries to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in a meeting with acting Kazakh Prime
Minister Akhmetzhan Smagulovich Yesimov, during which the two
leaders held comprehensive talks on furthering bilateral economic
and trade cooperation. (Kazakhstan-Chinese-Vice-Premier)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Phan Van Khai, 64, was elected Vietnam's new prime
minister and Nguyen Thi Binh was re-elected vice state president
at the National Assembly Thursday. (Vietnam-Premier)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Nikko Securities Co., one of Japan's "Big Four"
brokerage houses, was raided Thursday for alleged payoffs to a
corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
Nikko was said to provide racketeer Ryuichi Koike with 14
million yen (0.17 million U.S. dollars) in 1995, in violation of
Japan's Commercial Code and Securities and Exchange Law, according
to the Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office and the Securities
and Exchange Surveillance Commission. (Japan-Payoffs) 
</P>
</TEXT>
