<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Discusses Oil Imports With Saudi Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today discussed trade, especially oil imports,
with Saudi Arabian Second Deputy Prime Minister Prince Sultan Bin
Abdul Aziz in Cape Town, the South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a 20-minute meeting, Mandela said
there would be further talks on bilateral trade later today and
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, both men were tight-lipped on whether they touched
upon the widely reported 7-billion-Rand (1.5-billion-U.S. dollar)
arms deal between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he did not wish to disclose details at this
stage.
</P>
<P>
"We of course are great friends with Saudi Arabia and I can't
predict what will be discussed in the next few days," Mandela
said in response to a question about the arms deal.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the deal will involve the sale
of South Africa's G-6 self-propelled artillery systems and
anti-aircraft guns to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
As a counter-trade arrangement, South Africa was offering to
buy oil from Saudi Arabia, reports said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa now imports more than two-thirds of its fuel from
Iran and wants to reduce its reliance on that country, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince, who is also defense minister, will also meet
with South African Defense Minister Joe Modise and Mineral and
Energy Affairs Minister Penuell Maduna.
</P>
<P>
The prince arrived at midnight Wednesday in Cape Town after
technical problems of his plane delayed his scheduled arrival at
about 1 pm (1100 GMT).
</P>
<P>
A state banquet in honor of him on Wednesday night had to be
cancelled and Mandela held a private luncheon today instead.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is South Africa's largest trade partner in the
Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South African exports to Saudi Arabia were 364
million Rand (about 78 million dollars) and imports from the Gulf
state were 943 million Rand (about 200 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who has visited Saudi Arabia for at least three
times, will go to Riyadh again in November, according to SAPA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
