<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Inflation Slightly Down in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
inflation rate has dropped by 0.4 percent in August owing to
lower food prices, Central Statistical Service (CSS) figures
released today showed.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index dropped to 8.7 percent in August from
the disappointing 9.1 percent in July, South African Press
Association quoted CSS as saying.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the monthly food consumer price index was
attributed to lower prices of meat, fats and oils and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The monthly increase for all items excluding food was 0.3
percent, largely due to higher prices for alcoholic and
non-alcoholic beverages, cigarettes, cigars and tobacco, and fuel
and power.
</P>
<P>
Kimberley, a city 450 km southwest of Johannesburg, saw the
highest inflation rate of 10.5 percent, while the lowest rate of
6.9 percent was reported for the Free State goldfields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
