<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Calls for Peaceful Solution to African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier
and Minister of Foreign Affairs Qian Qichen today called on the
parties concerned in African Countries to settle conflicts and
disputes through consultation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that owing to historical reasons and
various complex internal and external factors, the situation in
Africa remained fluid. Particularly, since the beginning of this
year, local turmoil and conflicts had occurred form time to time.
</P>
<P>
Qian said with abundant natural resources and great potential
for economic development, Africa was an integral part of world
economy. There could be no world peace without stability in
Africa. Nor could there be prosperity in the world without the
development of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China heartily rejoiced over the positive changes in
Africa and appealed to the parties concerned in those African
countries caught in civil strifes to set store by the fundamental
interests of their countries and people, and settle the conflicts
and disputes through peaceful consultation so as to turn hostility
into friendship and restore peace and tranquillity to these
countries at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
China hoped that all ethnic groups and tribes in Africa would
strengthen their solidarity and work together for peace and
development in their respective countries, and China had supported
African countries on making their own choice of the political
system and the road to development in light of their respective
national conditions and opposed any external interference in the
internal affairs of African countries, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
China maintained that the international community, the United
Nations included, should pay attention to the African issues,
seriously consider the reasonable propositions and demands of
African Countries, including OAU, the Arab League and other
regional organizations, support and co-ordinate with African
countries in their efforts to safeguard regional peace and
security, and fully respect the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of African countries while handing their problems, Qian
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
