<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Chechnya Continue Tough Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The fourth round of talks
between the Russian Federation and the breakaway Chechen republic
on a comprehensive treaty began on Thursday, facing an uphill
struggle, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Secretary of Russia's Security Council Ivan
Rybkin, the parties of the negotiations insist on their positions.
Grozny is seeking an inter-state treaty, while Moscow -- a
power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin said that Moscow has prepared its proposals on the
treaty to be signed by Chechen leader Aslan Maskhadov and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, and the parties would also discuss the
agreements on joint defense and economic space.
</P>
<P>
Moscow proceeds from the standpoint that the Chechen republic
will be given maximum independence, maximum authority and maximum
freedom within the framework of the Russian Federation, Rybkin
said.
</P>
<P>
The key problem is about special status of Chechnya, he
emphasized and said that he had handed over a draft
Russian-Chechen power sharing treaty to Chechen negotiators at a
meeting of the joint Russian-Chechen commission in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
However, spokesman for the Chechen president Kazbek Khadzhiyev
said today that the preparation of an inter-state treaty with the
establishment of diplomatic relations as well as joint agreements
on defense and economic space is a clear position of the Chechen
delegation at the Moscow talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said "there can be no talk about power-sharing
between the federal center and Grozny at the negotiations."
"Russia and Chechnya are separate states," Khadzhiyev said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
