<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Wheat Production Better Than Estimated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) - World wheat production is put 2
million tons higher at 588 million tons, mainly resulting from an
increase in the figure for China, International Grains Council
(IGC) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of minor revisions for various countries
bring down the total for world trade by 1 million tons to 93
million tons, IGC said in an announcement.
</P>
<P>
Forecast exports are higher for Canada, but reduced for the EC
and the United States. The figure for world consumption is 2
million tons higher at 584 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Feed use is projected to rise to 98 million tons mainly because
of larger availabilities in Central/Eastern Europe, Russia and
other CIS countries, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
As far as coarse grains are concerned, higher estimated for the
EC, the Ukraine and Australia offset a reduction for the United
States, to raise the figure for world production by 2 million tons
to 877 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Despite updates for several importers in Far East Asia the
total for world trade remains at 92 million tons, IGC said.
</P>
<P>
Exports from China are forecast 0.5 million tons higher at 3.1
million tons, prompting a corresponding decrease in those from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Following minor adjustments to estimates for several countries,
IGC said, world coarse grains consumption is now put 3 million
higher at 895 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
