<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protocol on Beira Corridor on the Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe, Zambia, Mozambique
and Malawi are due to sign a memorandum of understanding before
the end of this year to pave way for the future development of
the Beira Corridor, a Zimbabwean minister said today.
</P>
<P>
The current Beira Corridor is a railway and road network
running between the Zimbabwean eastern border town of Mutare to
the Mozambican port city of Beira.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants to a symposium on the Beira Corridor
development in Mutare, Zimbabwean Transport and Energy Minister
Enos Chilowore said, following several meetings of the joint
technical unit, a draft memorandum of understanding was produced
and was currently being studied by the countries involved.
</P>
<P>
The joint technical unit comprising representatives of the
four southern African countries recommended that the draft
memorandum be considered at the committee of ministers meeting to
be held in Beira next month, Chilowore said.
</P>
<P>
"It is envisaged that the signing ceremony will take place in
Beira by the end of this year," the minister told 100 delegates
from business and government circles.
</P>
<P>
The corridor was envisaged to assist in the promotion of trade
and investment both in the southern African region and
internationally, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister lamented low levels of joint venture businesses
among southern African countries, saying this situation was as a
result of existing tariff and non-tariff barriers, fluctuating
border charges and rigid visa regimes which inhibited meaningful
trade and economic linkages in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
