<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Breaks out Between Somali Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting reportedly
broke out in Somalia between the militiamen of Hussein Mohamed
Aidid and those of the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) in and
around the important town of Baidoa on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the region said the fighting began at about noon
local time yesterday in the village of Qurunjis, 8 km south of
Baidoa, where the RRA maintain a strong militia base.
</P>
<P>
There are contradicting reports over the casualty figures
caused by this latest fierce fighting around the town of Baidoa,
245 km south of Mogadishu, the capital. Sources from the RRA
said at least 21 people were killed during the fighting which
continued until last night. The RRA admitted that their forces
have lost four fighters and seven others suffered gun shot
wounds.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the fighting broke out when the forces of the RRA
launched an attack on the Airport of Baidoa, destroying one of
Aidid's armed personnel carriers in the field. Mohamed Ali Aden
Qalinle, RRA spokesman here in Mogadishu, has claimed the upper
hand in the fighting. He said his forces were provoked by Hussein
Aidid's men at their base in Qurunjis, 8 km south of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
Other sources close to the militia commanders of Hussein
Aidid, put the number of fatalities to 9. However, there's no
independent confirmation regarding the opposing claims. The VHF
radios of Baidoa still remain out of the air since Wednesday
afternoon when the fighting had intensified.
</P>
<P>
There's no official word yet from Hussein Aidid's side over
the fighting. However, travellers from Ballidogle Airport, 90 km
south of Mogadishu, said they have seen large militia regrouping
at the airport which they thought would be a reinforcement plan
to Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
This new round of fighting is taking place at a time when
there is a large peace delegation touring the two regions of
the Rahanwein communities, Bay and Bakol. Radio South Mogadishu
supporting Hussein Aidid said last night that there has been
peaceful demonstrations in the region of Bakol in support for
the reconciliation among the Rahanwein people in the area led
by Sheikh Mukhtar Mohamed Hussein, a former parliament
spokesmen and a prestigious elder of the Rahanwein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
