<HEADLINE> Talks of Chinese, German Foreign Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen introduced China's
new opening policies to his German counterpart during a breakfast
meeting here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Qian was invited to the breakfast by Klans Kinkel, German Vice
Federal Chancellor and Foreign Minister. Both the host and guest
expressed their pleasure for the approaching 25th anniversary of
the establishment of the diplomatic relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their satisfaction for the positive growth
of the bilateral relations, saying that China and Germany have
good prospect for furthering their relations and enhancing their
cooperation in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Briefing Kinkel on the 15th National Congress of the Chinese
Communist Party, Qian said the Congress had worked out a blueprint
for China's development well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
China will push out new measures and take up different means to
exercise the public ownership, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to open its market and increase
exchanges with foreign countries in economic, trade and
technology. The country's service sector will also open to the
outside gradually and steadily, said the Chinese vice-premier.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said that China's new reforms and opening to the outside
world will add fresh strength to the cooperation between Germany
and China in such fields.
</P>
<P>
He said that Germany supports China's efforts to join the World
Trade Organization (WTO) at an earlier stage.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views on other international and regional
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
