<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Ruling Puts in Doubt 40 Years of Courts Martial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of British Service
personnel tried by courts martial since the 1950s could have their
convictions quashed after the system of British military law was
ruled unlawful by the European Court of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Strasbourg-based European Court ruled Wednesday that Paul
Coyne, an ex--corporal in the RAF, was unlawfully found guilty by
court martial in 1994 of forging a senior officer's signature to
obtain a large sum of money while serving in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Millions of pounds in damages may have to be paid by the
British Ministry of Defense (MoD) after the European Court found
court martial not to be "fair, independent or impartial,"
according to a report in today's Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
The Euro ruling applies to the courts martial procedures since
they were drawn up by the Army Act 1955 and raises the possibility
of a challenge to every decision up to April 1 this year when the
system was modernized.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers campaigning for an overhaul of British military law
welcomed the ruling as a significant victory but government
sources said that the reforms meant court martial had been made
fully lawful.
</P>
<P>
An MoD spokesman was quoted as saying: "On April 1, 1997,
Parliament brought into force reforms to the court-martial system
as part of the Armed Forces Act 1996."
</P>
<P>
"In the Government's view, the new arrangements are more than
adequate to ensure both the actual and apparent independence of
court martial as a tribunal and will enable the court-martial
system to continue to meet the Armed Forces requirement to
administer justice firmly but fairly," the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
