<HEADLINE> Chinese FM: China Attaches Importance to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- As a permanent member
of the Security Council, China had all along attached importance
to Africa, Qian Qichen, Chinese Vice-Premier and Minister of
Foreign Affairs, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Foreign Ministers' Meeting on Africa held by
the United Nations Security Council, Qian said China had supported
African countries in their just struggle for the maintenance of
national independence, state sovereignty and territorial
integrity, and in their efforts for economic rejuvenation and
social progress.
</P>
<P>
China had stood for the settlement of differences and conflicts
within Africa through peaceful consultation, and China believed
that African countries were fully capable of resolving their
internal conflicts and disputes, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the past years had seen visits to
Africa by the Chinese President, Premier and Vice-Premiers of the
State Council, and ministers, including Minister of foreign
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said China and African countries had made considerable
progress in their friendly relations and cooperation, and in the
years to come, China would continue to unswervingly support the
just propositions and reasonable demands of African countries,
strengthen its friendly relations and cooperation with them and
make its contribution to peace, stability and development in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Qian called for an early establishment of a just and equitable
new international political and economic order so as to create a
good external environment for the stability and sustained
development in Africa and to ensure a lasting peace and
development there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
