<HEADLINE> Detained Liberian Newspaper Editor Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Liberian police today released
the managing editor of a newspaper who had been arrested on
charge of buying stolen computers during unrest last year.
</P>
<P>
The police, which has been in high gear to crack down upon
armed robbery in the country, stormed the offices of Philip
Wesseh late Wednesday and arrested him.
</P>
<P>
Philip Wesseh was released several hours later in the night as
"the police have no clear evidence to prosecute him on charges of
criminal malevolence," said a senior police officer.
</P>
<P>
The police took Philip Wesseh away "because he has some criminal
charges to answer", said police chief Joe Tate, quoted by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Wesseh was accused of buying looted computers for his
newspaper in April last year when the most horrible factional
fighting in Liberia's seven-year-old civil war broke out in the
capital Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
The police suspected him to be involved in armed robbery, the
BBC said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, Wesseh denied the
allegation, saying his newspaper had bought some computers in the
United States, while others had been donated by a U.S.
humanitarian, Rev. Philip Saunders.
</P>
<P>
The inquirer was among many news organizations that were
torched by both rebels and police during the factional fighting,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of Wesseh without a warrant has led to some
criticism on the part of the police, but Tate reportedly said: "I
like criticism" because it could help improve his job.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
