<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New School Year Endangered in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A major rift among Sierra
Leone's teachers emerged today to threaten the beginning of the
new school year next month as staff disagreed over whether they
want to work under a military government.
</P>
<P>
The military administration, which came to to power in May
after ousting the legitimate government through a coup, has
announced that primary school classes will resume on October 6
and secondary education on October 19.
</P>
<P>
But the National Executive Committee of the 18,000-strong
Sierra Leone Teachers' Union (SLTU) issued a response calling on
members to "ignore both dates and continue their stay-home
defiance".
</P>
<P>
All schools and universities have been closed since the May 25
coup, affecting almost 150,000 pupils and students, according to
a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The SLTU executive committee said last week that staff should
only go back to work if the military returns power to the
civilian government and if all outstanding salaries and
allowances of teachers are paid in full.
</P>
<P>
However, a committee of concerned teachers has rejected the
stance,issuing a statement saying that the "majority of
teachers are ready to serve the nation in conjunction with any
government of the day."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
