<HEADLINE> European Shares down on Weak Wall Street, Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
ended mainly lower Thursday, undermined by a weaker dollar, Wall
Street's opening losses and strong US economic data which made it
possible for US to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index in London ended down 0.23 percent or
11.7 points at 5,065.5, but above the day's worst levels.
</P>
<P>
Volume was swollen by a Shell dividend options related deal,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The market showed little reaction to Britain's global and
non-European-Union trade figures, which saw smaller than forecast
deficits.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index on the Frankfurt market which ends before Wall
Street opens, ended more than one percent or 46 points higher at
4,148.58, supported by a stable dollar and strong car stocks,
although dealers said trading was thin.
</P>
<P>
However, in later screen-based trade the IBIS DAX index ended
46.02 points down at 4,104.93, depressed by a weaker Dow, a
further fall by the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed 18.39 points lower at 3,005.38
on profit-taking and a fresh downturn on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
But losses were checked by relief that the French government's
1998 budget draft law contained nothing unexpected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
