<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Defends Settlement Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel today defended its
decision to build 300 housing units in the Efrat settlement in
southwestern Jerusalem, arguing it was resulted from the "natural
growth" of population.
</P>
<P>
Moshe Fogel, director of the Government Press Office, told
reporters that the housing plan was definitely within the boundary
of the existing settlement and did not constitute the construction
of a new one.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced Wednesday
night that Israel would build 300 more housing units in Efrat and
areas around it.
</P>
<P>
Fogel, who is also the Israeli government spokesman, said the
plan was originally approved by the previous Labor government,
which later decided to freeze settlement activities to push
forward peace negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to comment on whether the settlement decision
implied a refusal to the request by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright for a "time-out" of unilateral actions by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
During her first Mideast trip early this month, Albright called
on both Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to
refrain from taking unilateral steps that are detrimental to
reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Efrat settlement project has sparked strong reactions from
the U.S. and the PNA who warn against repercussions on peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin has quoted Albright
as saying that the new housing plan would not contribute to the
calming of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA President Yasser Arafat's adviser Ahmed Tibi
today described the plan as a "land mine" on the road towards
peace.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition politicians also rose to attack the new
housing project, saying it could ruin the chances for peace.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid blasted Netanyahu for quelling any
new hopes for peace whenever they emerge.
</P>
<P>
High-level talks are expected to be held in New York between
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Arafat's deputy in the PNA
Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) on exploring ways to reactivate the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peacemaking has been deadlocked since March
when Israel started building Har Homa settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem, that the Palestinians want as the capital of a future
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
