<HEADLINE> Mozambican Army Should be Country Builder: Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's military forces
should be a peace maker and country builder at the same time,
noted Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Maputo Heroes' Square marking the 33rd
anniversary of the founding of the Mozambican People's Liberation
Army, Joaquim Chissano, the Mozambican president and Commander In
Chief of the army, said that "liberation does not merely mean the
raising of the national flag, what it means more is the struggle
to build the country."
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the facts that some southern African
countries were purchasing weapons, Chissano said that there were
no enemy in the region, so the military forces should not be
developed in this consideration.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulations letter to the army Wednesday, Chissano
said that at the time dominated by peace, military forces should
never be regarded as a war machine, but should be seen as an
impetus for peace and development.
</P>
<P>
He called for a united and disciplined army with virtue of
respecting human beings.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said that during his recent tours to the central
Mozambican province of Sofala and the southern province of
Inhambane, he saw people enjoying stability and economic
development. The big efforts made by the Mozambican people to
build their country in the past 33 years since independence are
worthwhile, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mateus Ngonhamo, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Mozambican Defense
Forces, said Wednesday that apart from safeguarding the nation's
sovereignty and interests, the army should have a close
relationship with the people in their effort to develop the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
On September 25, 1964, Mozambican people fired the first shot
in their struggle for national independence from the colonial
rule in Chai district of Cabo Delgado Province.
</P>
<P>
The day was named as Mozambican People's Liberation Force Day
in 1975 when Mozambique won its independence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
