<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Lifts Virus Alarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- German health authorities today
corrected their earlier suspicion that the death of a Ghanaian man
last weekend in a German hospital could be traced back to an
infection of the Lassa virus.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ghanaian died on Saturday in the western German
city of Mainz after admitting himself to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
He had been suspected of dying of the deadly Lassa fever which
regularly hits regions of West Africa and could claim the lives of
up to 40 percent of those infected. The Lassa virus is
transmissible through rat urine or human body fluids including
sweat.
</P>
<P>
But the Health Ministry of the western German state of
Rhineland-Palatinate said today that two blood tests at a Hamburg
institute had confirmed that the man had not died of the Lassa
fever, or any other highly infectious disease like Ebola.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the ministry also stopped the the medical
supervision on about 120 people who had come into contact with the
Ghanaian.
</P>
<P>
The actual reason for the man's death will be announced after
the autopsy results come out on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends Astronaut to Russia's Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) today announced that
American astronaut David Wolf will blast off for the Russian space
station Mir on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wolf, 41, will spend the rest of this year aboard Mir because
the mission poses no "unnecessary peril," NASA administrator
Daniel Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
Wolf was scheduled to blast off with the rest of the crew of
space shuttle Atlantis at 10:34 p.m. EDT for a rendezvous with the
troubled Russian space station.
</P>
<P>
The problems on Mir include a collision with another
spacecraft, a fire and repeated computer failures, Goldin said at
a press conference at the headquarters of NASA here.
</P>
<P>
Goldin said his decision to go ahead with the joint
U.S.-Russian program was informed by independent reviews of the
station's safety.
</P>
<P>
"I have concluded shuttle-Mir (program) has a thorough review
process that ensures continued American participation on board Mir
and does not put human life in unnecessary peril," Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision should be based and is based on scientific and
technical assessment of the mission's safety and the agency's
ability to gain additional experience and knowledge that cannot be
gained elsewhere," he added.
</P>
<P>
Goldin said that besides reviewing three separate reports on
Mir's fitness, he talked to Wolf.
</P>
<P>
Citing that 20-minute conversation, Goldin said Wolf felt the
risk of the shuttle's ascent was greater than the risk aboard Mir,
but that this was an acceptable risk.
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't wish to inflict this pain on any human being,"
Goldin said of the decision-making process. "I don't sleep nights
and there's only one thing on my mind, for weeks now: the safety
of our American astronauts."
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. congressmen and scientists oppose Wolf's space trip
arguing that it is not safe as so many problems have appeared in
the Mir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0044 </DOCNO>
