<HEADLINE> Egypt Bans Media Coverage on Fatal Bus Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman from Egypt's
Interior Ministry explained today that the reason behind the ban
on reporting the deadly bus attack in downtown Cairo is to
facilitate investigations into the crime that killed 10 people.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the explanation in a telephone conversation
with Volkhard Windfuhr, Chairman of the Cairo Foreign Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
"This restriction aims at speeding up and facilitating the
ongoing investigations," Windfuhr said in a letter faxed to Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
The ban issued Wednesday at the request of the Interior
Ministry applies to "all Egyptian and foreign media and
journalists based in or visiting Egypt," Windfuhr said. It
requests reporters "to refrain from covering and publishing any
items related in any form to the military court's investigations,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The September 18 attack killed nine German tourists and an
Egyptian driver.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, concerned over the impact of the recent attack on its
tourist industry, has repeatedly described the attack as an
isolated act instead of an organized crime targeting tourists. It
also warned against any "overstatement" by the media coverage.
</P>
<P>
The military prosecution taking over the case from the state
security Monday night has begun probings with the two suspects,
Saber Mohamed Farahat and his brother Mahmoud Farahat.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak last weekend ordered the transfer of
the case to military prosecutors, who handle most of the cases
involving Muslim militants who have been fighting a five-year
violent war against the secular government.
</P>
<P>
The case is expected to be referred next month to a military
judiciary court, where cases can usually have a speedy trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Parliament Discussing Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan parliament started
debate today on constitutional reforms bill under which some laws
charged as "oppressive" will be repealed and the power of the
president reduced before the impending general elections.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Attorney-General Amos Wako, when presenting the bill to
the 200-seat parliament, said the bill is based on the reform
package drafted two weeks ago by lawmakers from both the ruling
Kenya Africa National Union ( KANU ) and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The bill will repeal the law allowing detention without trial,
allow political parties to hold party meetings without licenses
and opposition parliamentary members to visit their constituents
without permits.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Broadcasting Corporation (KBC) was compelled over
the new law to air variant views and to allocate free air time to
registered political parties during elections, said Wako.
</P>
<P>
The law banning certain publications considered unpalatable in
the country will also be amended, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bill demands that the government either registers all
political parties or formally declines to do so within 120 days.
And the political party which is denied to registration has right
to launch an appeal to the high court.
</P>
<P>
A committee in charge of drafting further reforms package on
constitution after the election and within the next two years
will be established under the bill.
</P>
<P>
Although the bill contains no big changes, it would provide a
more stable and level play field for the elections in which
74-year-old President Daniel arap Moi, the country's president
since 1978, is widely believed to win, KANU lawmaker Gerald
Ndwiga told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
It will take the 200-seat parliament, where KANU enjoys a
majority, about three weeks to get the bill reach the third
reading and finally decide whether to translate it into law,
Ndwiga added.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere has considerably eased in the country
since the KANU and the opposition formed an inter-parties
parliamentary group and reached consensus on minimum
constitutional reforms earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0046 </DOCNO>
