<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Bank Sees Better Chance for Euro's Punctual Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Researchers of Germany's largest
commercial bank, the Deutsche Bank, today said that they are
expecting a 80 percent chance for the punctual start of the
planned single European currency, the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Deutsche Bank researchers also believed that the Euro could
come in 1999 with a large participation, including Germany,
France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Austria, Ireland,
Finland, Spain, Portugal as well as Italy.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of Italy, however, would still depend on its
implementation of the 1998 budget plan and its social reform
plans, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to the researchers, the Euro's outlook have been
improved particularly by the strengthening political support from
Germany as well as France's 1998 budget plan.
</P>
<P>
After a heated Euro debate during the summer, most of German
politicians now apparently moved to support a punctual start of
the Euro, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 1998 budget plan also boosted France's chances
to cut its budget deficit next year to less than 3 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP) as required by the Euro standards,
the German researchers added. They also predicted that France
might also be able to move close to the 3-percent target this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Works to Tap Farming Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has given priority to
investment in the agricultural sector in a bid to tap its vast
farming potential.
</P>
<P>
Bwalya Ng'andu, Director-General of Zambia's authoritative
investment center disclosed in Lusaka Wednesday that the center
has drafted policies to encourage investment flows into the
undeveloped sector, an English newspaper The Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
according to Ng'andu, investors are allowed to import all
agricultural implements free of duty, which is a fairly
attractive incentive.
</P>
<P>
Scondly,the agricultural income flow is taxed at a lower level
of 15 percent and the machinery can be depreciated within two
years. This means that a farmer can write off the full value of
equipment within two years, charging 50 percent in the second
year.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, investors in agriculture are also entitled to
developmental allowances.
</P>
<P>
Through implementation of these new policies, the Zambian
government hopes the country, which highly relies on copper
exports, can become the " breadbasket" of Southern Africa due to
its existing vast potential.
</P>
<P>
The government also expects Zambia to become an ideal
investment location and the agricultural sector to become a
growing point in the single-product economy.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is a landlocked country with a population of about 9
million and a territory of 752600 square kilometers. Apart from
its mineral deposits, its main resource is cultivatable land.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 9 million hectares of cultivatable land, only
1.44 million hectares has been exploited up to now.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's tropical climate, modified by altitude, is
comparatively moderate. This makes it possible to grow any
tropical or sub-tropical crops, vegetables and horticultural
products.
</P>
<P>
Zambia also has plenty of water resources, covering 45 percent
of water resources in Southern Africa. Abundant water in rivers,
lakes, and underground water readily available and reasonable
rainfall, allows the country for continuous irrigation.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia is one country where anything grows. If you finger in
the ground and water it, it will probably grow," said Ng'andu,
when joking about the country's farming potential.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
