<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian: China Willing to Enhance Ties with GCC States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- China is willing to
further enhance its cooperation with the nations of the Gulf
Cooperation Council for the Arab States (GCC) in all the fields,
said Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen here
today.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks during his meeting with foreign ministers
and representatives from the six GCC member states -- Bahrain,
Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates --
at the headquarters of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
They are here attending the 52nd session of the U.N. General
Assembly which opened on September 16. Senior officials from China
and the GCC countries hold regular meetings and dialogues each
year at the U.N. sessions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the two sides said that such dialogues show
that both sides are willing to enhance their mutual trust and
cooperation and they should make full play of such mechanism to
push forward their long-term, stable and comprehensive partnership
of cooperation in view of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the cooperation between China and the GCC in
trade and economy has developed well in recent years. The two
sides have the potentiality in further cooperation in all the
fields including economy, energy, science and technology, finance,
information as well as management.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent successful convention of the National
Congress of the Communist Party of China and Hong Kong's return to
the motherland have increased the opportunities for China to
expand its economic and trade relations with other nations. He
hoped that the government and enterprises in China and the GCC
nations could make greater efforts for the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
GCC ministers agreed with Qian and expressed their strong will
to further their economic and trade cooperation with China. They
said they will work together with China to seek new opportunities
for cooperation in economy, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
On the Gulf situation, Qian stressed that China, as one of the
members of the U.N. Security Council, has always attached
importance to safeguarding peace and stability in the Gulf region.
It is willing to increase its dialogues and cooperation with the
Gulf countries in this area.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministers expressed welcome and thanks to China for the
stance.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Qian noted that China is
deeply concerned with the troubled peace process in the region,
and hopes for an early restart of the process.
</P>
<P>
He said China holds that the U.N. resolutions on the Middle
East should be fully observed; the principle of "land for peace"
should be adhered to; all the parties should continue to implement
every agreement that has already been reached; and all the forms
of terrorism should be opposed.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the common goal for the people of
every nation in the world, the Chinese vice-premier said. China is
willing to work together with the international community for a
lasting peace and stability in the Middle East, stated Qian.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated the GCC's efforts toward this goal.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministers said that the Gulf countries value and
appreciate China's constructive role in the international affairs,
expecting China to continue its positive role in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed other international and regional
issues during their meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
