<HEADLINE> Albright Renews Call for Freeze on Jewish Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said today that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's latest decision to build a new Jewish settlement in
the West Bank was "unhelpful" for peace and renewed her call for a
freeze on any such provocative move.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu announced Wednesday that there will be 300 more
Jewish homes in construction in Efrat in the West Bank. The
announcement came less than two weeks after Albright urged Israel
to take a "time out" from expanding settlement during her trip to
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a U.N. press conference, Albright said, "We have
made it quite clear that this particular building is not at all
helpful as we try to get the peace process going again."
</P>
<P>
"I am calling across the board again for a time out on actions
that make it more difficult to have successful negotiations,"
Albright added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said it was very important to have a good environment
for peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians, but
Netanyahu's latest actions "make it more complicated to have us
act in a role that we would like to, to bring the parties together
in order to have successful negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been blocked since March
when Netanyahu broke ground on a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem, seen by Palestinians as the capital of a future state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
