<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Reversing Resegregation Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton today appealed to Americans to reverse a trend toward
resegregation when speaking at a ceremony to marked the 40th
anniversary of the day when nine black students integrated a
Little Rock high school in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
"Far too many communities are all-white, all-black, all-Latino,
all-Asian. Indeed too many Americans of all races have actually
begun to give up on the idea of integration, and the search for
common ground," news reports quoted Clinton as telling a crowd
gathered outside the front steps of Central High School.
</P>
<P>
On September 25, 1957, a group of students now known as "the
Little Rock Nine" desegregated the school under the presence of
Army troops enforcing a court order.
</P>
<P>
The black students were taunted and spat on by angry whites
when they attended school.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a podium in front of the doorway that the nine
students entered, Clinton said that 40 years ago today, the Little
Rock Nine "climbed these steps, passed through this door and moved
our nation, and for that we must all thank them."
</P>
<P>
"What happened here changed the course of our country forever,"
he said. "For surely it was here at Central High that we took
another giant step closer to the idea of America."
</P>
<P>
But there was much work left to be done, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"Today children of every race walk through the same door, but
then they walk through different halls, not only in this school
but across America, they sit in different classrooms, they eat at
different tables, they even sit in different parts of the
bleachers at the football game," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a trend toward rolling back affirmative action programs
granting preferences to minorities in education "is slamming shut
the doors of higher education on a new generation."
</P>
<P>
"Segregation is no longer the law, but too often separation is
still the rule," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He said "there is still discrimination in America," and "it is
wrong, and we have to keep working on it, not just with our voices
but with our laws, and we have to engage each other in it."
</P>
<P>
After he spoke, the now middle-aged Little Rock Nine walked up
the steps to the sound of applause, and walked into the school
with Clinton holding open the door in a symbolic gesture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Existing Home Sales Up to Four-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned
homes in the U.S. rose by 3.3 percent in August to the highest
level in nearly four years, according to a report from the U.S.
National Association of Realtors made public today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that existing homes sold at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 4.32 million in the month, the highest
since December 1993,
</P>
<P>
The increase followed a revised 4.18 million unit rate in July
and many economists had expected a slight drop in home sales in
August.
</P>
<P>
The report had been scheduled for release Friday. But it was
reported in a newsletter and confirmed by the Realtors today.
</P>
<P>
By region, sales rose 6.5 percent in the West, 4.4 percent in
the South, 3.3 percent in the Midwest. But they fell 4.8 percent
in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, sales of the existing homes for the first eight
months of this year totaled 4.16 million, up 1.8 percent from the
same period of last year. Total sales in 1996 were the best in 18
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
