<HEADLINE> Pentagon Defends Its Probe in Gulf War Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense
Department today said that it opposes the removal of its role in
the Gulf War illnesses probe, defending its way in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"The Pentagon is fully capable of conducting its own
investigation," Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters,
acknowledging that early Pentagon investigations were not handled
well.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen praised Defense Department staffers for "an
extraordinary effort" in the past year. "I think Dr. Rostker has
done a superb job," he said. Bernard Rostker is the Pentagon's top
official dealing with the subject.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion to hand over the investigation to a committee
outside the Pentagon is contained in a draft of a report that a
White House advisory committee is scheduled to give to President
Clinton by October 31.
</P>
<P>
The committee reportedly said the Pentagon's credibility
continues to erode and another agency or outside body could better
handle investigation into the matter.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon called the White House draft
disappointing considering the volume of work and research the
Pentagon has done in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon "will continue to be as open as we can on this,"
he said. "We do not oppose oversight.... We do oppose taking it
away from the Pentagon and giving to a medical school or some
other agency," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
Rostker said, "It's a very unfair rap to say, `You were bad in
'94, and therefore you can't be trusted again.'... I've been at
this for a year, and I just do not buy the story about
credibility."
</P>
<P>
He said he has conducted 13 in-depth investigations into
specific events where potential exposure might have occurred and
has met around the country with veterans and their organizations,
members of Congress and the news media.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Gulf War veterans suffer from a syndrome varying
from joint aches to an eyesight loss. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
