<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US FTC Launches Antitrust Investigation on Intel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Trade
Commission is investigating whether Intel Corp. violated the
antitrust law by trying to monopolize the market for computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
The FTC notified the company about the investigation Wednesday
and it was the second time in less than five years that the U.S.
government probes the largest chip-makers in the world, The Wall
Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Intel, based in Santa Clara, California, makes the
microprocessors that are the brains of 85 percent of all personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
Intel said its lawyers were reviewing subpoenas and would
cooperate with the FTC.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. FTC said it wanted to determine if Intel had acted "to
monopolize, attempt to monopolize or otherwise restrict price or
non-price competition in the development or sale of microprocessor
or other computer components or related intellectual property."
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, the FTC conducted a similar investigation, then
declared that no additional action was called for and that the
probe was closed. Intel said it expects the new investigation will
end the same way.
</P>
<P>
The FTC probe follows Intel's planned 420 million-dollar
purchase of Chips &AMP; Technologies Inc., a maker of graphics chips.
Some graphics-chips companies have expressed concern about Intel's
entry into the market.
</P>
<P>
In its latest acquisition, Intel said this week it would buy
Dayna Communications, a small Salt Lake City-based maker of
hardware that helps link together computers in networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
