<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Criticize Textbook For Use In Taiwan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Experts here today strongly
criticized a textbook compiled by Taiwan authorities because of
its distortion of history and attempting to split the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The textbook, titled "Understanding Taiwan", was published in
February and was used on a trial basis for grade-one middle school
students in Taiwan in September. It has three volumes, dealing
with history, society, and geography.
</P>
<P>
Members of China's National Review Committee of Textbooks for
Primary and Middle Schools pointed out that the new textbook
distorted history, deliberately cut links between Taiwan and the
mainland, and prettified Japan's colonial rule in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this was to instill a notion of separating
Taiwan from the mainland and Taiwan as an "independent political
entity" in the minds of young people, in an attempt to seek
"Taiwan independence", critics said.
</P>
<P>
Since ancient times, they pointed out, Taiwan has been an
inseparable part of China and the ethnic groups in Taiwan have
been members of the Chinese nation as a big family. People across
the Straits have been as closely linked as flesh and blood,
sharing the same Chinese culture. The people in the mainland and
the Taiwan compatriots have joined hands and made brilliant
contributions to the development and construction of Taiwan, the
critic said.
</P>
<P>
However, the textbook disregards history and says not a single
word about the Chinese nation and Chinese civilization, but vainly
attempts to replace them with so-called "Taiwanese" and "Taiwan
Spirit".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Considers Use of Spy Service to Monitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- German government today
confirmed that it was considering authorization for the country's
foreign intelligence service to monitor Scientologists abroad.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman made the confirmation after the
Sueddeutsche Zeitung newspaper reported such a move could lead to
international complications with Washington.
</P>
<P>
"In the Unites States... senior intelligence service officials
belong to Scientology," said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Final decision has yet to be made on the issue. The idea was
criticized today by the opposition Greens Party during a
parliamentary debate on sects, which it said could intensify the
conflict with Washington over Scientology's treatment.
</P>
<P>
Scientology has been put under surveillance by domestic
security service in Germany after interior ministers from the
country's 16 federal states decided earlier this year that the
organization posed a possible threat to democracy.
</P>
<P>
This move groups Scientologists with the country's neo-Nazi and
extreme leftist parties.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Senator Alfonse D'Amato has accused Germany of restricting
freedom of religion with regard to Scientology. In response,
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said last Monday the claims
were "intolerable" to a free country as Germany and that
Scientology was a business and not a religion.
</P>
<P>
He also described Scientology as a "quasi-totalitarian"
organization.
</P>
<P>
Following Kinkel's statement, the United Nations announced that
it would look into the Scientology issue in Germany and present a
report to the UN Human Rights Commission in the next spring.
</P>
<P>
German politicians stressed the treatment to Scientology came
as a result of the country's historic experiences.
</P>
<P>
Roland Kohn, a deputy for the Free Democratic Party, a
coalition partner in the Bonn government, said, "In Germany we
have a concept of defensive democracy: no freedom for the enemies
of freedom regardless of whether they appear in the guise of
religion or not." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
