<HEADLINE> Canada's Industrial Product Price Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada's industrial product
price index rose 0.7 percent in August following two months of
decline, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the increase was due to the rise in the value of
the U.S. dollar, the federal statistics agency noted.
</P>
<P>
The August increase in the value of the U.S. dollar against the
Canadian dollar raised the value in Canadian dollars of all export
prices quoted in the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
This increased the month-to-month change in industrial prices
from 0.4 percent to 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In August, the most significant industrial price change in
Canada was the overall price level for gasoline and fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
Other price changes of note were those for exported motor
vehicles, some non-ferrous metals, and pulp and paper products.
</P>
<P>
The 12-month change in Canada's industrial prices remained at
0.9 percent for a third consecutive month in August, the agency
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
