<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Mobile Phone Services Complain About New Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian mobile telephone
operators have complained about a government plan to impose a tax
on cellular network, saying that would raise call prices by more
than a half and undermine the industry.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian parliament gave an approval on September 17 to a
draft legislation charging mobile operators 19 cents for each
minute of network traffic. The rates for domestic calls now range
from 0.5 to 25 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian Mobile Communications (UMC) said that about 40
percent of its potential clients would be lost after the tax is
imposed. UMC offers mobile telephone services based on the NMT-450
and GSM-900 standards.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time our government is trying to impose an
excise tax on a service rather than a commodity," said Valeriy
Posnikov, spokesman for Golden Telecom, which operates a GSM-1800
cellular telephone network in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Both firms warned that the tax would cost rather than earn
money for the government due to a shrinking market.
</P>
<P>
Posnikov estimated a treasury loss of 8.3 million dollars in
value-added and corporate income taxes as mobile calls would
decrease following introduction of the tax.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the U.S.-based Motorola Company cancelled a
plan to invest 500 million dollars in its own cellular phone
network in Ukraine for fear of the government's constant rule
changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
