<HEADLINE> US Senate Begins Debating Campaign Finance Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today
began debating a long-stalled proposal to change the way campaigns
are financed.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and Democrat legislators have been
pressuring the Republican-led Congress to debate the issue, while
Senator Mitch McConnell, head of the National Republican
Senatorial Campaign Committee, has vowed to kill the reform
proposal.
</P>
<P>
That bipartisan bill, written by Republican Senator John McCain
and Democratic Senator Russell Feingold, would ban so-called
"soft" donations that are largely unregulated and can be used only
for generic party activities.
</P>
<P>
The alleged misuse of "soft" money last year by both parties is
one of the central aspects of current controversy.
</P>
<P>
Democrats had expected to wait weeks for the proposal to be
brought up after securing Republicans' consent Tuesday to consider
it. However, Senate Republican leader Trent Lott pushed it quickly
to the floor in a clear attempt to blunt criticism that
Republicans were obstructing the proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
