<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Criticise Taiwan Textbook (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The textbook also debases normal exchanges across the Taiwan
Straits, putting on a par the migration of the people from the
mainland to develop Taiwan and the invasion of Taiwan by the
Netherlands, Spain and Japan, calling the latter "international
competition", the critics pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In talking about the Japanese invasion of Taiwan and its
colonial rule, the book not only plays down the hardships of the
compatriots across the Straits in their fight for Taiwan's return
to the motherland, but also sings praise of Japan's cruel rule and
plundering, and prettifies the period of Japanese colonial rule by
calling it a time of promoting Taiwan's modernization.
</P>
<P>
Critics pointed out that, under the pretext of introducing
local culture to students, the textbook actually attempts to
spread the idea of splitting the motherland, and will only harm
younger generations.
</P>
<P>
The attempt to split the motherland by using the textbook
compiled by a small number of people in Taiwan have met with
strong opposition from the people of Taiwan. Some Taiwanese with
greater insight have written articles criticising the splittist
plots and calling for a revision of the book.
</P>
<P>
Critics here called on Taiwan authorities to respect history,
conform to the will of the Chinese people, and make a thorough
revision of the book.
</P>
<P>
They also expect Taiwan counterparts in education to edit
textbooks to follow the principle of seeking truth from facts,
being responsible for the young and for the future of the Chinese
nation and safeguard the unification of the motherland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
