<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economy Gains at 3.3 Percent Rate in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy increased
at an annual rate of 3.3 percent in the second quarter of this
year, according to a revised report released today by the U.S.
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the gross domestic product (GDP) -- the sum of
all goods and services produced within U.S. borders -- was down
from a torrid 4.9 percent rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the deceleration mainly resulted from the
sharp drop of consumer spending, which accounts for about
two-thirds of the U.S. economy. The spending slowed from a 5.3
percent growth rate in the first quarter to just 0.9 percent in
the second.
</P>
<P>
But businesses kept the economy advancing at a healthy rate by
building their inventories and investing in new equipment at the
fastest rate in 14 years. Businesses investment on capital
equipment soared at a 23 percent annual rate, the highest since
the fourth quarter of 1983.
</P>
<P>
The real change in business inventories added a 0.8 percent
percentage point to the second-quarter change in real GDP after
adding 1.8 percentage points to the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Exports of goods and services increased by 18.4 percent in the
second quarter, comparing with an increase of 9.9 percent in the
first. Imports increased by 20.5 percent, comparing with a gain of
17.9 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The overall 3.3 percent growth rate represents a revision from
the 3.6 percent estimate announced a month ago. Smaller export
growth than shown last month is the primary source of the
revision.
</P>
<P>
The various changes put the U.S. economy's output in the second
quarter at a seasonally and inflation-adjusted annual rate of 7.16
trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that inflation has been well behaved and
analysts now believe that the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) will hold
rates steady when its policy-makers meet Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A measure of inflation tied to the GDP rose at a mere 1.8
percent annual rate in the second quarter, the smallest in five
years and down from 2.4 percent in the first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
