<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright rebuked
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for promising to build
300 new homes on the West Bank. She has repeatedly called for a
"time out" unilaterally provocative actions like new construction
in disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
-- The House and Senate passed a spending bill that would open
an avenue for President Clinton to extend the stay of American
troops in Bosnia, where a crucial voting is scheduled for autumn.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Speaker Newt Gingrich ruled out any chance that the House
would pass the major bipartisan proposal for overhauling campaign
finance that has been advanced in the senate. The Senate majority
leader Trent Lott suddenly decided to bring up campaign fiance
legislation for floor debate Friday, weeks earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration will seek new powers that would
allow federal inspectors to block imports of fresh fruits and
vegetables that don't meet U.S. food safety standards. The
proposal, to be announced next week, is one element of a four-part
administration program aimed at improving the safety of both
foreign and domestic produce.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Tobacco firms would pay penalties based on how popular their
brands were among underage smokers under a proposal by Health and
Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala. The company-by-company
proposal was as specific as Shalala got during testimony before
the Senate labor panel about President Clinton's plan for
toughening the proposed national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton commemorated a crucial early civil-rights victory by
holding open the door of central High School in Little Rock, Ark.,
for nine African-Americans who braved a gantlet of treats and
racial taunts to integrate the school 40 years ago. The president
said that while segregation has been outlawed, "too often it is
still the rule." 
</P>
</TEXT>
