<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Fail to Reach Aviation Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the United States
failed to reach an aviation agreement at a renewed round of talks
ended here today, but agreed to hold the next round in Washington
in the week starting October 20, Japanese officials said here.
</P>
<P>
During the current talks beginning Monday, the U.S. negotiators
sought a transitional agreement to break the impasse while
shelving their long-held demand for complete liberalization of
route selections, frequencies and flights between and through the
two countries, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Complete liberalization means giving U.S. and Japanese
airliners freedom to decide on flight routes, capacity and
frequencies as long as certain criteria like safety and slot
limitations are met.
</P>
<P>
Japan opposes the concept, which it says would enable the more
competitive U.S. airliners to dominate the potentially lucrative
Asia-Pacific market.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, U.S. negotiators also urged Tokyo to allow 91
new weekly flights, but Japan insisted on permitting only 70,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides failed to eliminate differences on
how to calculate the number of passengers and other flight
standards in a third-country, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, referring to the next round of talks, Japanese vice
transport minister Hiromichi Toya who led the Japanese team, said
he is not certain whether any agreement could be reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
