<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar to Host Doha Summit As Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Doha, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Qatar will host the fourth
Middle East and North Africa (MENA) summit as scheduled on
November 16-18 despite a possible boycott by some Arab countries,
informed sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that Doha remained firm on convening the
conference as scheduled," said a diplomat here who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
"Though some of Arab countries will boycott the summit, other
Arab states are expected to send delegates to Doha, but at a
lower level," he added.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
have announced their boycott of the summit due to Israeli
participation, Many Arab states would most likely send businessmen
instead of governmental delegations to Doha.
</P>
<P>
He said a recent decision by the Arab League kept the
possibility even much bigger and left Qatar determined to host the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made by the Arab League during an Arab foreign
ministers' meeting held last week in Cairo, granted Arab
countries rights of making free choices, instead of a concerted
boycott.
</P>
<P>
"Qatar was satisfied with the decision. Its worries about a
joint boycott have gone away," he said.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the conference are underway and the Qatari
Ministry of Information has received nearly 600 applications from
journalists in and outside the country to cover the event.
</P>
<P>
The controversial summit to include Arab states, Israel and
their partners in the industrialized world was launched in
1994. Its last session took place in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Lebanon and the PNA voiced boycott of the summit in
protest against the deadlock in the Middle East peace
process. They had boycotted all the previous three.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia also favored a
boycott, saying they would not appear at the conference unless
major achievements are made in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Most of other Arab states adopt a wait-and-see stance towards
the summit. Qatar officials said they have not received any
refusal from these countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
