<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to be World's "Oldest" by 2020 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan, with 31 percent of its
population aging 60 or more by the year 2020, will become the
"oldest" country by then.
</P>
<P>
It will be followed by Germany, Greece, Italy and
Switzerland, all expected to have over 27 percent of aging
population, said a press release today by the World Health
Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
World's aging population will double from 540 million now to
more than one billion by 2020, with the number living in
developing countries rising from the present 330 million to 710
million, the press release showed.
</P>
<P>
Europe will continue to be the "oldest" region in the world,
with people 60 years old or more reaching 20 percent in 2020 from
19 percent today.
</P>
<P>
The proportions of aging people in other regions will
also rise. For instance, North America's proportion of people 60
years old or more will increase to 23 percent and East Asia's to
17 percent.
</P>
<P>
To mark the annual International Day of Older People on October
1, WHO is launching activities around the world to bring attention
to the need to invest in health throughout a person's lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
