<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Chirac Hold Talks in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin today said that there are no differences between Russia
and France on international as well as bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after meeting with his French counterpart
Jacques Chirac, who is currently on a three-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that Yeltsin expressed deep
satisfaction with the results of their talks, saying "we do not
have a single difference."
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two presidents exchanged views on a
variety of issues including the formation of a Russian-French
university, the annual education of 1,000 Russians in France, the
registration of former Soviet property for the benefit of Russia
and others.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also met with Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, and discussed with him joint investment and economic
projects.
</P>
<P>
Chirac shared Yeltsin's views on the international issues and
praised Russia's efforts in building a market economy, saying the
implementation of the joint projects "will certainly strengthen
the bilateral ties between the two countries." 
</P>
