<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Bahamian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said today that China treasures its relations with the Bahamas and
is ready to cooperate with the Bahamian side in promoting the
steady development of bilateral friendly and cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang extended a warm welcome to visiting Bahamian Prime
Minister Hubert Ingraham, and asked that he convey best wishes to
Bahamian Governor-General Orville Turnquest.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President noted that Ingraham's visit to China
shortly after the establishment of Sino-Bahamian diplomatic
relations is a true indication that the Bahamian government and
prime minister attach great importance to the development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the current China tour will enhance mutual
understanding and friendship and will lay a solid foundation for
furthering bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
China and the Bahamas, both of which are developing nations,
share similar historical experiences and both are faced with the
tasks of national economic development, improving the living
standards of their people and safeguarding world peace, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, according to Jiang, Ingraham resolutely
decided that the Bahamas would "sever diplomatic ties" with
Taiwan and establish diplomatic relations with the People's
Republic of China. Jiang expressed his sincere appreciation for
the Bahamian decision.
</P>
<P>
"China has consistently held that all countries, big or small,
strong or weak and regarless of geographical locations, should be
equal members of the international community," said Jiang. "We
believe that bilateral relations based on the Five Principles of
Peaceful Coexistence will enjoy smooth development."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Bahamas gained independence 20-odd years ago
and has since made unremitting efforts to safeguard its national
independence and sovereignty, revitalize its national economy and
improve the living standards of its people. He also noted the
achievements the nation has scored in related efforts.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that the Bahamas has pursued a policy of
nonalignment, tried to promote friendly cooperative ties with
other countries, positively promoted the integration process in
Latin America and the Caribbean, and is playing an increasingly
important role in regional issues.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope your country will continue to record new
achievements in various fields," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Ingraham noted his pleasure in visiting China and meeting Jiang
so soon after the two nations forged diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
"I expect to gain a better understanding of China and to
further enhance friendly bilateral relations and cooperation
through this historical visit," said Ingraham.
</P>
<P>
Ingraham briefed Jiang on cultural and education undertakings
in his country, and expressed the hope that the two nations will
increase exchanges, especially exchanges between high-ranking
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Jiang briefed Ingraham on the convocation of the 15th National
Congress of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC), with the latter
congratulating the Chinese president on the successful congress
and his reelection as General-Secretary of the CPC Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Hu Xijie, chairman of the Chinese Government Reception
Committee and vice-minister of Communications, and Bahamian
Foreign Minister Janet Bostwick also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ingraham is the first Bahamian prime minister to visit China
since the two nations established diplomatic relations in May this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
