<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Acts to Mitigate Impact of El Nino Phenomenon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has stepped up
measures to mitigate the impact of the El Nino weather phenomenon
on agriculture, Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a national consultative conference on
socio-economic development presided by President Fidel Ramos,
Escudero said the measures being taken by the government include
cloud-seeding, fast-tracking of irrigation projects and
construction of small water-impounding facilities and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, multisectoral task forces have already been
organized at the regional, provincial and municipal levels
nationwide to help implement government strategies to minimize the
impact of the expected dry spell, he said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a recurrent global climate abnormality that can
cause prolonged dry season and drought or excessive rainfall in
short periods.
</P>
<P>
Escudero said the government has also launched an information
drive on El Nino, water conservation and other measures to lessen
the harsh impact of the abnormal weather pattern.
</P>
<P>
The government is giving priority to El Nino-related projects
that could be completed in 18 months such as the repair of
irrigation dams and canals and the installation of additional
shallow tube wells.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
