<HEADLINE> Plane Crash Kills 248 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- 248 people including crew
members were feared to have been killed today in the crash of
Indonesia's Garuda Airbus a-300 jetliner near Medan, North
Sumatra, TV Republic Indonesia (TVRI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed at Mountain Sibolangit, about 40 kilometers
west of Medan, capital of North Sumatra Province at around 1:15
p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The passengers aboard the plane included two Americans and six
Japanese, Antara News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Medan Police, Col. Primanto, confirmed the crash
and said the plane came from Jakarta's Soekarno-Hatta Airport and
was on its way to Medan's Polonia Airport.
</P>
<P>
He said Polonia air traffickers lost contact with the plane
about 30 minutes before the plane was to land at the airport at
1:45 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Medan's search and rescue team has been sent to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
The accident was feared to have been caused by the haze coming
from raging forest fires in Sumatra Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
