<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Establish National Health Education Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China plans to establish a
nationwide health education network covering all urban areas and
80 percent of rural areas by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The network will be composed of health education institutes at
different levels and medicare agencies, as well as departments in
charge of publicity, radio and television broadcasting, education,
culture, family planning and the welfare of women.
</P>
<P>
Educational work will focus on food hygiene, maternal and
infant health care, student health, anti-smoking and the
prevention of infectious and chronic diseases, according to an
on-going national conference on health education.
</P>
<P>
Conferees are discussing a long-term program for the next 12
years, and will urge all provinces and prefectures, and 90 percent
of counties to establish health education institutes by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The conferees suggested that 70 percent of township hospitals
should employ health education specialists, and noted that the
network should be expanded to all counties and 95 percent of
townships in 2010.
</P>
<P>
The National Patriotic Public Health Campaign Committee and the
Ministry of Health, sponsors of the education drive, will
introduce a series of quotas to evaluate educational work in
different parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The quotas will be used to measure knowledge levels and
evaluate the effectiveness of efforts to prevent disease and
promote personal health care.
</P>
<P>
"Health education will be the focus of our efforts to deal with
major public health problems in future," according to Minister of
Health Chen Minzhang. He added that similar measures adopted in
other countries have proved highly effective.
</P>
<P>
Chen pointed out that various chronic diseases, such as
cardiovascular and cerebral diseases, malignant tumors and
diabetes, are emerging as the major health threats to Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
Chen warned that China will face serious health problems
resulting from environmental pollution and industrialization by
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
"We will use preventive measures as the main method for
reducing related problems," said Chen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
