<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Decline as Industrials Lose Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished slightly lower today, with industrial stocks losing
ground as investors switched to major resource companies.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said higher metal prices helped boost resource stocks,
with bargain hunters picking up stocks in morning trade and then
cashing in profits in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 3.6 points down at 2,775.6,
after taking its lead in morning trading on the fall on Wall
Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP topped turnover with 26.432 million shares
traded at the value of 412.9 million Australian dollars (297.2
million U.S. dollars). Shares in BHP gained 24 cents to rise to
16.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the strong performance of the BHP's share price
could be on expectations that all the bad news is out.
</P>
<P>
Mining giant WMC also had strong turnover with 10.352 million
shares traded at the value of 51.11 million U.S. dollars. Shares
in WMC gained 17.5 cents to climb to 6.42 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto, another mining giant, lost 5.5 cents to fall to
20.63 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was down 22.4 points at 4,588.5 and
the all resources index was up 13 points at 1,346.2.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Foster's Brewing Group dropped 8.8 cents or 2.96
percent to 2.883 Australian dollars on a turnover of 3.2 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
In the interest rate-sensitive banking sector, National
Australia Bank fell four cents to 22.36 Australian dollars on a
turnover of 10.09 million shares. Commonwealth Bank of Australia
dropped 14.7 cents to 17.073 Australian dollars, ANZ Banking Group
climbed one cent to 11.45 Australian dollars and Westpac Banking
Corp went down nine cents at 8.74 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 387.65 million shares valued at 1.628
billion Australian dollars (1.172 billion U.S. dollars). Rises of
582 outnumbered falls of 537.
</P>
<P>
The rise in the New York price of gold bullion helped lift the
gold index up 27.2 points to 1,281.3.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trading in gold bullion, closed up at 326.05 U.S.
dollars an ounce, compared to Thursday's close of 323.30 U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
