<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf States, EU Closer to Free Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Doha, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab states and their main
trade partner, the European Union (EU), have made headway in a
much-awaited planned free trade zone to boost trade relations.
</P>
<P>
According to a local newspaper report today, the two sides
have ironed out most of their differences at two rounds of
negotiations this year and agreed to hold three more rounds on
1998, before an agreement can be initialed.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari weekly Gulf Times quoted unidentified Gulf officials
as saying progress was achieved after the six Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) nations edged closer to setting up a customs union,
a prerequisite set by the EU for their free trade pact.
</P>
<P>
"At their talks in Riyadh on June 12, the GCC and the EU
delegates discussed the draft free trade agreement and the EU
agreed on most modifications sought by the GCC," the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said the two partners had removed more
than 80 percent of the hurdles blocking a free trade agreement,
under discussions by the two sides for more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Such issues as more EU investment in the Gulf, the environment
and customs tariffs will be settled at the coming talks, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The EU has repeatedly told GCC countries they must unify their
widely varied tariffs before it signs the free trade pact, which
the GCC has sought in a bid to boost exports to the EU and attract
industrial technology.
</P>
<P>
However, GCC states, which control nearly 45 percent of the
world's recoverable oil reserves, argue such a pact is justified
because they do not impose tariffs on most EU products and want
reciprocal treatment.
</P>
<P>
But the EU has voiced fears that removal of duties on Gulf
petrochemical and other exports altogether could result in
dumping European markets with cheap products and threaten the
EU's independent petrochemical industry.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed in 1994 on a gradual removal of the
tariffs but the EU said more negotiations were needed before a
pact is finalized. The absence of a free trade agreement has
combind with lower oil prices and a sharp rise in EU exports to
the Gulf to upset the trade balance between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
From a large surplus in favor of the GCC in the early 1980s,
the balance sharply tilted in favor of the EU, which had a surplus
in the trade of goods and services of around 10.9 billion in
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruin of Indonesia's Crashed Plane Found in Ravine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The ruin of Indonesia's
Garuda Airbus A-300 jetliner, which crashed at around 1:35 p.m.
local time near Medan, North Sumatra, was found in a
500-meter-deep ravine five kilometers away from Medan-Brastagi
highway.
</P>
<P>
The passengers aboard the plane included two American and six
Japanese nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus carrying 222 passengers and 12 crew members crashed
at Mountain Sibelangit, about 40 kilometers west of Medan, capital
of North Sumatra province, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Medan police, Col. Primanto, confirmed the crash
and said the plane came from Jakarta's Soekarno-Hatta airport and
was on its way to Medan's Polonia airport.
</P>
<P>
He said Polonia air traffickers lost contact with the plane
about 30 minutes before the plane was to land at the airport at
1:45 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
There was no report on the fate of passengers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
Medan's search and rescue team has been sent to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
The accident was feared to have been caused by the haze coming
from raging forest fires in Sumatra island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
