<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Plane Crash Feared to Be Caused by Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Airbus crash
today was feared to have been caused by the haze coming from
raging forest fires in Sumatra island, TV Indonesia reported.
</P>
<P>
A Garuda Airbus A-300 jetliner carrying 222 passengers and crew
members crashed at Mountain Sibelangit near Medan, capital of
North Sumatra province, Indonesia, this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred in Pancur Batu village in North Sumatran
district of Deli Serdang, some 40 kilometers west of Medan, Antara
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Medan police, Col. Primanto, confirmed the crash
and said the plane came from Jakarta's Soekarno-Hatta airport and
was on its way to Medan's Polonia airport.
</P>
<P>
He said Polonia air traffickers lost contact with the plane
about 30 minutes before the plane was to land at the airport at
1:45 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
There was no report on the fate of both passengers and crew
members.
</P>
<P>
Medan's search and rescue team has been sent to the crash site.
</P>
