<HEADLINE> Mandela Predicts Boost of S. Africa's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today that the contribution of tourism to the
country's economy could be doubled.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism's contribution to our economy could be doubled at
least from its present 4.5 percent and it has the potential to
create hundreds of thousands of jobs," the president said when
launching a new blue train in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"Government, the private sector and our communities are
working together to realize this potential," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, together with international celebrities from all over
the world and government officials, embarked on a luxury
Pretoria-Cape Town journey on board the new train to boost
tourism and at the same time raise money for his children's fund.
</P>
<P>
"The blue train is a part of the plan to boost sustainable
tourism in South Africa. It has great potential to become one of
the flagships of this growing industry," he said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
It shows that South Africa is ready to meet the exacting
standards of quality and service required in the highly
competitive market of luxury rail travel, he said.
</P>
<P>
The renovated train is said to be the most luxurious in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The train, which was refurbished at a cost of 70 million Rand
(14.9 million U. S. Dollars), is 380 meters long, has 18
carriages.
</P>
<P>
Besides comforts like audio and video, each compartment has
its own bathroom, with either a bath or shower, a telephone,
television and individually controlled air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
The new train will also benefit the tourism sector in Zimbabwe
as it also goes to the Victoria Falls and Hwange in that country.
</P>
<P>
"This is a fine example of how linking the strengths of
neighboring countries brings mutual benefits. It is a real
contribution to the development of southern African tourism,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is an important part of South Africa's economy.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan said earlier this week that
tourism could generate 40 billion Rand (8.5 billion dollars)
annually and create 2 million jobs if its contribution to the GDP
were raised to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"No other industry has such potential," Jordan told a
conference of the Airlines Association of Southern Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
