<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Cabinet Approves Budget for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
today approved a budget bill for 1998 totalling 75.56 trillion won
(about 84 US billion dollars), up 5.8 percent compared to that of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, per capita tax will increase from 1.95
million won (about 2,133 US dollars) in 1997 to 2.17 million won
(about 2,374 dollars) next year and the tax revenue will account
for 21.4 percent of the national income, rising from the 21.2
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The bill, to be submitted to the National Assembly for approval
by October 2, includes the general account budget of 70.36
trillion won (about 77 billion dollars) and the special account
budget of 5.2 trillion won (about 5.7 billion dollars), increasing
4.1 percent and 36.1 percent respectively compared with the 1997
budget.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1998 budget, defense expenditures will grow 6.2
percent to 15.24 trillion won (about 16.7 billion dollars),
slightly higher than the average growth rate but the lowest growth
rate since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Investment in economic infrastructure will increase 10.8
percent to 11.2 trillion won (about 12.3 billion dollars),
including 619.7 billion won (about 678 million dollars) earmarked
for part of the construction of the Seoul-Pusan high-speed railway.
</P>
<P>
Educational spending will rise 8.1 percent to 20.1 trillion won
(about 22 billion dollars), of which some one trillion won (about
1.1 billion dollars) will be raised by local governments through
issuing municipal or provincial bonds for investment in local
education and the 10-percent education tax increase.
</P>
<P>
Educational investment in the country is expected to reach a
total of more than 23 trillion won (about 25 billion dollars) next
year, representing five percent of the gross national product.
</P>
<P>
Outlays for environmental protection will also surge 15.6
percent to 2.51 trillion won (about 2.75 billion dollars), while
social welfare spending will rise 12.3 percent to 4.8 trillion won
(about 5.25 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
