<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Australian Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government was in crisis today with Prime Minister John Howard
announcing he had sacked two of his senior staff and accepted the
resignation of a third minister over mistaken travel claims in
less than a week's time.
</P>
<P>
Howard announced that federal Science Minister Peter McGauran
resigned today after admitting to mistaken travel claims.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also told a news conference that he had
sacked two of his staff members, senior political adviser Grahame
Morris and office manager Fiona McKenna. Howard blamed the two
staff members for what he called their failure to inform him of
the mistaken travel claims.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press said the loss of Morris, who
masterminded Howard's 1996 election victory, is certain to prove
the greatest blow to Howard in a personal and political sense.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters if it was difficult to sack his closest
adviser, the prime minister said: "it's been a very difficult day
... it's a very sad day."
</P>
<P>
McGauran came under fire after admitting to parliament
yesterday he wrongfully claimed about 1,008 US dollars in travel
allowances from 1996.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Administrative Services Minister David Jull and
Transport Minister John Sharp also resigned after it was revealed
that Sharp had secretly repaid almost 9,000 Australian dollars
(6,480 US dollars) in travel claims.
</P>
<P>
Howard described this week as a difficult and painful one.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament last night that one of Jull's staff claimed
to have told Morris and McKenna about the repayment in May.
</P>
<P>
But today the prime minister stood by his claims that he knew
nothing about the secretly paid-back travel claims until the last
few days.
</P>
<P>
"Neither of them (Morris nor McKenna) had any discussions with
me about these matters until the last few days," Howard told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no one was alleging that he was involved in
any cover-up.
</P>
<P>
Federal Opposition leader Kim Beazley today called for a
judicial inquiry into what he called the cover-up of Sharp's
repayment of 6,480 US dollars in travel entitlements.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader called on Howard to stand aside during
the inquiry and "it is not sufficient any longer to simply rely on
the prime minister's word in this regard, a judicial inquiry is
necessary."  
</P>
</TEXT>
