<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Reject Compulsory Savings Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Over 90 percent of the New
Zealanders have said no to the compulsory savings scheme proposed
by the New Zealand First party to replace superannuation.
</P>
<P>
Provisional results coming out tonight show that of the 1.72
million votes counted, 92.4 percent oppose the scheme while only
7.6 percent favor it.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.84 votes have been received in the referendum on
the compulsory savings scheme starting on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed scheme, New Zealanders earning over 5,000 NZ
dollars (3,200 US dollars) a year will have to put aside 3 percent
of their income for retirement. The savings target is 120,000
dollars, but the government will top it up for those who cannot
reach the target.
</P>
<P>
With the savings, people will buy an annuity which is expected
to be at the same size as today's pension.
</P>
<P>
A no vote has been expected as opposition to the scheme came
from most of the social sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
