<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0930 GMT, September 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Among 208 Ugandans arrested recently in Kenya, 114
have been released since the Ugandan Foreign Ministry intervened,
a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Rebecca Kadaga, the state minister in Foreign Ministry in
charge of regional cooperation, told "The New Vision" that the
relations between Uganda and Kenya are good.
</P>
<P>
The remained 94 other arrested Ugandans reportedly have no
valid documents or have expired documents. The state minister said
she doubted if they are all Ugandan civilians. (Uganda-Release)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The military junta in Sierra Leone has suffered a
fresh setback as ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah has been
accredited as leader of a national delegation to the United
Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
President Kahhah, ousted in the May 25 coup, will address the
General Assembly on behalf of his country on October 1, according
to press reports today. (SLeon-Kabbah-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- An earthquake rocked Italy's central region of Umbria
early this morning, killing at least two people and injuring more
than 10, a radio report said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, which was centered to the north of the Foligno
city, was measured 5.5 on the Richter scale, Italy's National
Geophysical Institute said. (Italy-Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The United State's Southern Command in Panama
Thursday moved from here to Miami, Florida, ending its 34-year
residence in this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
General Charles William, who was appointed the commander of the
military headquarters Wednesday morning, announced the movement
plan at a brief departure ceremony during which time the American
flag was lowered.
</P>
<P>
More than 770 military and nonmilitary people, the last batch
of the headquarters' personnel, will depart for Miami
today. (US-Panama)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. space shuttle Atlantis blasted off for
the Russian Mir space station late Thursday with American
astronaut David Wolf.
</P>
<P>
Administrator Daniel Goldin of the U.S. National Aeronautics
and Space Administration (NASA) Thursday approved Wolf's
four-month mission despite pressure on him to back out before of
the safety problems on Mir. (US-Space Shuttle-Blast-off) 
