<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Holds Talks with Bahamian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today that the establishment of Sino-Bahamian diplomatic
relations has laid a political basis for the two countries to
advance bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks while meeting with visiting Prime Minister
Hubert A. Ingraham of the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Ingraham's current China tour, the first from a
Bahamian prime minister since the country won independence, would
increase mutual understanding and promote Sino-Bahamian
cooperation in every field.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Sino-Bahamian diplomatic relations in May
marked a new phase of the bilateral relationship, Li noted, adding
that China appreciates the decision made by Ingraham to forge
diplomatic relations with China, which showed the prime minister's
far-sightedness.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the trade between China and the Bahamas
has already started and large-scale investment from
enterprises in China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and
its inland areas has been put into the Bahamas. China is ready to
explore the fields and means of economic collaboration with the
Bahamas according to the international practise, he added.
</P>
<P>
The relations between China and the Caribbean countries have
witnessed new development in recent years, Li told Ingraham. China
has set up diplomatic ties with the Bahamas and Saint Lucia,
established trade representative offices in Haiti
and the Dominican Republic and joined the Caribbean Development
Bank, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The premier stressed that it is China's consistent policy to
expand its friendly and cooperative relations with Latin American
and Caribbean nations, which would serve the common interests
of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Ingraham said he is pleased to visit China soon after the
Bahamas and China forged diplomatic ties, which he described as a
major event in bilateral links. The Bahamian people support their
government's decision to establish diplomatic relations with China
and they are looking forward to greater development of the ties
between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that China, as a big country, has always respected
other countries' sovereignty and independence, especially those of
the small countries like the Bahamas. The Bahamian government and
people appreciate the fact that China never interferes in other
countries' internal affairs, Ingraham told Li.
</P>
<P>
The Bahamas highly praises the six proposals put forward by
Premier Li Peng in his speech at the annual meeting of the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund, Ingraham
said. These proposals protect the interests of the developing
countries and have outlined the principles that should be observed
in setting up rational international relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reiterated that his country would stick to
the "one China" policy and would not have any kind of official
relations with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Following the talks, the two sides signed an agreement on
economic and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Li Peng presided over a welcome ceremony in
honor of the Bahamian prime minister, who arrived here yesterday
afternoon for a week-long official visit to China at Li's
invitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
