<HEADLINE> Irrigation Changes China's Farming Methods (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Irrigation has brought great
changes to north China's Loess Plateau, the most arid area in the
country, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The large number of cisterns dotting the region's once barren
land store valuable rainwater used for greenhouses filled with
mushrooms and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Localities in this vast arid area, especially Gansu province,
and the Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous regions which
receive limited annual rainfall of between 350-500 mm, have
introduced measures to construct cisterns and use efficient
water-saving technology to store rainwater needed to irrigate
crops during dry seasons.
</P>
<P>
Related irrigation techniques have effectively increased
cultivated land by nearly 40,000 ha. In addition, Gansu plans to
reclaim another 166,000 ha of wastelands and turn them into
irrigated high-yield fields by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation has greatly altered the traditional cropping system
in north China, according to agronomists, who noted that the new
farming method can serve as a worldwide model for properly using
rainwater in arid areas.
</P>
<P>
However, storing rainwater for irrigation is still in its early
stage, and the vast renewable resource is far from being fully
utilized. The annual rainfall in parts of central and eastern
Gansu and southern Ningxia equal annual runoff entering the Yellow
River, China's second longest river following the Yangtze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irrigation Changes China's Farming Methods (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experimental projects in central Gansu show that irrigating
formerly barren farmland will produce yields of some 1,500 kg of
wheat per ha. in normal years, The figure will double with the use
of plastic sheeting alone, and will top 4,000 kg. by combining the
use of both methods.
</P>
<P>
Rainwater irrigation has brought rapid economic development to
the arid area where serious water shortages long bottlenecked
local agriculture and forced people to lead a hard life.
</P>
<P>
The central government introduced a program to build large
water conservancy projects in the area in the 1950s, with water
diversion projects transforming formerly parched land into
irrigated fields.
</P>
<P>
Water tankers introduced to combat drought were ineffective in
rugged arid mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation offers great prospects for agriculture on over two
million sq.km. of arid land in north China, said one American
agronomist, adding "I've climbed the Great Wall twice, and feel
that this project is virtually on the same scale."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
