<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels to Boycott Talks With Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) today warned it will boycott the peace
talks with the Philippine government set for next month if
agreements signed between the two sides are not complied with.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, gave
no specific reason in a statement for the decision but hinted that
the talks are useless if the government is not implementing the
agreements signed on September 3 and 12.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently assessing the compliance of the
government with the agreements on troops repositioning and
administrative guidelines for a general truce signed by members of
the government-MILF subcommittee on the cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar believes the government is not complying with the
agreement especially on its pledge to bring back safely evacuees
in Pikit, the southern province of Cotabato, to their respective
villages.
</P>
<P>
Several evacuees were quoted by him as saying that despite the
agreement on the repositioning of troops, some of them who
returned home found government troopers, especially policemen,
still remain in the positions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Major General Raul Urgello, chief of the Army's
Sixth Infantry Division, denied Jaafar's allegation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over a local radio station, Urgello said that the
government has complied with the spirit of the agreement regarding
troops repositioning.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said the MILF's decision not to resume the
talks could break the hairline boundary between relative peace and
war here in the future.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest anti-government Muslim force
operating in the southern Philippines, with an estimated 25,000
armed members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
