<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Build Its First Science Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
approved the construction of a science park so as to create an
enabling environment to nurture and promote the application of
technological innovations, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The facility, the first in the country, is drafted jointly by
the International Center for Insect Physiology and Ecology
(ICIPE) and the Export Processing Zones Authority (EPZA) with a
number of Kenya's leading science institutions, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The park, called ICIPE Technopark, will cover 7.2 hectares in
Nairobi and be constructed in four phases over 10 years starting
January 1998. The whole cost is estimated to reach 500,000 U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
It will offer a number of business development services aimed
at supporting new and established enterprises especially those
using bio-technology for the processing, manufacture and
marketing of products such as pesticides, vaccines and insect
traps.
</P>
<P>
The services include quality assurance and improvement in the
production process with due consideration to environmental issues
such as the reduction in waste generation and maximizing the use
of energy.
</P>
<P>
Other services include promotional activities and product
awareness campaigns, entrepreneurial workshops and seminars,
market feasibility studies and consumer surveys.
</P>
<P>
The park will also provide biotechnology laboratory analytical
services and facilities for technology exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
ICIPE plans to commercialize its research findings through the
high-tech park after more than a quarter century of research on
human health, agriculture and livestock development in Africa,
said ICIPE Director-general Hans Herrens.
</P>
<P>
EPZA Chief Executive Silas Ita said he expects a fruitful and
dynamic partnership between his authority, the government, ICIPE,
the universities and the business community in promoting local
technology in this east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers Offered Higher Allowances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
announced a major increase in teachers' allowances ranging from
15 to 100 percent in a bid to avert the strike set for October 1,
the "Daily Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Kenyan Education Minister Joseph
Kamotho as saying on Thursday that the allowances' increase was
in addition to salary increment ranging between 10 and 28
percent, which was announced early this month.
</P>
<P>
The new allowances will cost the Kenyan government an
additional 1.2 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 20 million U.S.
Dollars) a month on top of 2.3 billion Shillings (about 38
million Dollars) paid to teachers monthly.
</P>
<P>
The minister appealed to teachers throughout the country to
accept the new allowances, saying that under the present economic
circumstances, it was the best the ministry can offer to
teachers.
</P>
<P>
Under the new arrangements, the lowest paid teacher who gets a
basic salary of 1,880 Shillings (about 30 Dollars) a month will
get a house allowance of 841 Shillings monthly while the highest
paid teacher with a minimum basic salary of 21,000 Shillings will
get a house allowance of 6,000 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Kamotho noted that six out of the 11 members of the Teachers
Service Recommendation Committee had accepted the new salaries
and allowances given by the government.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT) issued
a seven-day strike notice, saying that teachers of the country
would down their tools on October 1 if their demands were not met
by September 30.
</P>
<P>
KNUT Secretary-General Ambrose Adongu said on the same day
that the strike would go on if the recommendation of the Teachers
Service Review Commission (TSRC) will not have been implemented
in full at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The TSRC recommended a salary increase ranging between 150 and
200 percent for the teachers, but the government agreed to give
the teachers an increment ranging between 10 and 28 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
