<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Hits Vietnam's Central Coastal Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Tropical typhoon hit Vietnam's
three central coastal provinces on Wednesday night and early
Thursday morning, killing two people and injuring 27 others, local
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon damaged houses, power lines, trees and rice fields,
said the latest report from the National Centre for
Hydro-Meteorological Forecast.
</P>
<P>
Areas south of Da Nang City and the coastal Quang Nam Province
were the center of the tropical storm, which brought torrential
rains and winds of up to 100 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Thua Thien-Hue, Da Nang, Quang Nam and Quang Ngai were the most
seriously affected areas, with more than 1,000 houses and many
schools being destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Rivers in the Thua Thien-Hue Province rose to alarming levels,
as the Huong River rose up to 1.95 meters and the Bo River to 2.18
meters, submerging rice fields.
</P>
<P>
A strong whirlwind also struck the City of Hue, injuring 18
people, destroying 80 houses and bringing down many electricity
poles and trees.
</P>
<P>
Some seven fishing boats sank and three others were destroyed
near Ly Son Island off the Quang Ngai Province.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon has weakened to a low depression, moving to the
west. 
</P>
</TEXT>
