<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Fruit Dealers Urged to Form Alliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 26 (Xinhua) -- African exporters of processed
fruit and vegetables are being encouraged to form strategic alliances
with European buyers to penetrate the otherwise over-supplied and
sometimes fickle European market.
</P>
<P>
The African fruit and vegetable processors were also advised to
identify niche markets and concentrate on labor-intensive products
where they enjoy a comparative advantage, according to a report
from Nyanga in east Zimbabwe today.
</P>
<P>
African exporters and European importers of fruit and
vegetables agreed at the end of a four-day meeting there Thursday
there is need for local exporters to develop expertise within the
local and regional markets before venturing into Europe.
</P>
<P>
The meeting organized by the Brussels-based Center for the
Development of Industry (CDI), an EU-ACP body, and the Zimbabwe
Investment Center sought to find ways of increasing the volume of
eastern and southern African horticultural produce entering the
European market.
</P>
<P>
however, after presentations by consultants and face-to-face
talks among entrepreneurs from both continents, it emerged that
there would be little chance for a dramatic increase in African
exports of fruit and vegetables to the European Union (EU)
countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegates said, ''the EU market is generally well-supplied in
all products capable of being produced from this region", except
those "out of season fresh produce.''
</P>
<P>
''The best way is to establish a long-term relationship with
the buyer and plan development together -- with requirement
known, quality assured, continuity guaranteed and prices
attractive,'' the participants agreed.
</P>
<P>
The CDI said progress in negotiations should be informed
timely to the exporters and importers so that they would be in a
better position to assist should the need arise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Denmark Ink Investment Promotion Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Denmark
signed an agreement on the promotion and reciprocal protection of
investments here, a news release from the Presidential Palace said
today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which seeks to create mutually favorable
conditions for investments and to intensify cooperation between
private enterprises of the two countries, was signed on Thursday
by Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista and Poul
Nielson, Minister for Development and Cooperation of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, each country shall admit investments by
investors of the other country in accordance with its legislative
and administrative practices and encourage such investments,
including facilitating the establishment of representative
offices.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that investments by each country shall at all
times enjoy full protection and security in the territory of the
other country.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between the Philippines and Denmark averaged 50
million US dollars since 1990, with Denmark consistently enjoying
a favorable trade balance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
