<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Has Enough Money to Pay Ex-fighters: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's budget will not be
affected by the government decision to pay an unbudgeted 3.5
billion Zimbabwe Dollars gratuity to ex-freedom fighters as there
are other alternative sources of raising revenue.
</P>
<P>
This was declared by acting Finance Minister Emmerson
Mnangagwa during a debate on the Finance Ministry's budget in
parliament on Thursday, referring to the sum of about 309.7
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has "more than adequate funds" to pay
the gratuities for about 70,000 ex-fighters.
</P>
<P>
"This budget presented in July will be carried and maintained
as structured as at the time of delivery," he said, adding that
"we have sufficient means and resources outside the budget to
meet the requirements of the ex-combatants."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the government has the unallocated reserve
of 5.7 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (more than 500 million U.S.
Dollars), which is a contingent facility to cushion the country
against unforeseen developments like droughts.
</P>
<P>
He said the unallocated reserve is only to be used in the
event of urgent and critical shortages in the budget. Parliament
should have authority to disburse the unallocated reserve.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came hard on the heels of a World Bank decision to
withhold more than 700 million Zimbabwe Dollars (less than 70
million U.S. Dollars) to finance Zimbabwe's economic reform
measures.
</P>
<P>
According to economists, 3.5 billion Zimbabwe Dollars
represents over five percent of the government's total annual
expenditure and would raise the anticipated deficit for the
period to December 31 next year of 8.9 percent of GDP to over 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe's post-budget commitment to pay each
ex-fighter a 50,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (about 4,425 US Dollars)
lump sum gratuity by December followed a series of nationwide
demonstrations by ex-freedom fighters who accused the government
of relegating them to poverty.
</P>
<P>
Besides access to free health and education, the ex-combatants
will also be entitled to a monthly pension of 2,000 Zimbabwe
Dollars (less than 200 U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
