<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain, Iran to Normalize Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain and Iran have
agreed to normalize their diplomatic relations, 15 months after
they lowered their diplomatic representation to charge
d'affaires level, a report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA said that Tehran and Manama
have agreed to expand their bilateral ties through a fresh
approach and "are to introduce their respective ambassadors to
Manama and Tehran shortly."
</P>
<P>
The report said that the agreement was reached between Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi his Bahrain counterpart Sheikh
Mohammad bin Mubarak al-Khalifa in New York Thursday when they had
talks on the sidelines of the current annual session of the
U.N. General Assembly there.
</P>
<P>
The Bahrain foreign minister called the exchange of ambassadors
as an important action in strengthening bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic crisis between Manama and Tehran began in June
1996 after Bahrain accused Iran of being involved in a plot
to overthrow the Bahraini government by supporting pro-Tehran
Islamic groups. 29 Bahrainis had confessed to planning to topple
the ruling family and establish an Iranian-style government in the
gulf country.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain had first quietly withdrew its ambassador from Tehran
and then Iran had to recall its ambassador from Manama.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Al-Khalifa in the meeting with
Kharrazi expressed willingness of his country in establishing
friendly relations and realizing further cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister said in the meeting that
promoting ties with neighboring countries as well as contributing
to further establishment of regional security are high on the
list of Iran's foreign policy priorities.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that cooperation among regional countries in
political, economic and cultural affairs could help bring about
a climate of trust and good neighboring feelings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kharrazi also had a talk with UAE Foreign Minister
Rashid Abdollahof in New York on Thursday and the two sides
explored ways and means of creating an atmosphere of
understanding and consolidating bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not mention their territorial dispute
over the three islands in the Persian Gulf, which are
controlled by Tehran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
