<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Maintain Upward Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Strong demand for superfine
wool helped keep prices higher this week, the Australian Council
of Wool Exporters said in its market review today.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator rose 12 cents to close at 722
Australian cents (519 US cents) a clean kg while the western
market indicator gained nine cents to close at 600 Australian
cents (432 US cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The council said 63,076 bales were offered at sales in
Newcastle, Melbourne and Fremantle this week with a pass-in rate
of 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The main focus of competition was on the superfine offering
and other finer wool in the 20 micron and finer categories, as is
reflected by price movements for the various micron categories,"
the review said.
</P>
<P>
"Strong Italian and Japanese demand for the superfine offering
in Newcastle and Melbourne led the market," it said.
</P>
<P>
"With the exception of China, competition for the week as a
whole was quite widespread, although reports continue to indicate
that, while pipeline demand remains strong, trade in tops and yarn
remains quiet and does not reflect recent movements in greasy wool
prices."
</P>
<P>
About 73,200 bales are rostered for sale in Sydney and
Melbourne next week, the council said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
