<HEADLINE> Orbis International Helps Blind Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Orbis International (OI), a
traveling eye hospital based out of an airplane, has landed in
east China's Anhui Province to provide free eye surgeries for
local people and training for oculists.
</P>
<P>
During its 20-day stay in Anhui, OI plans to operate on more
than 70 patients suffering from cataract and train some 500 local
eye doctors free of charge. It has already donated medical
equipment and informational videotapes to the provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
Anhui has about 400,000 people with eye disease who have no
access to treatment, though about 60,000 patients with cataracts
have regained their eyesight over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
OI, which arrived in Anhui earlier this month, is a non-profit
organization offering information on the prevention of eye
diseases and eye surgery, and education for medical communities
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 patients worldwide have benefited from the
help of over 600 Orbis doctors. 
</P>
