<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Live Longer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Life expectancy in Uganda
has risen to 50.4 now from 47 years in 1990, reported local daily
"The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-chancellor of Makerere University John Ssebuwufu was
quoted as saying that the rise was due to advances in technology.
</P>
<P>
He said, Ugandans with access to safe drinking water between
1990 and 1996 accounted for 62 percent of the entire population.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, is attributed to higher access to health
services of about 51 percent in 1997 and to adult literacy rates
about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, a report released by the United Nations Population
Fund last year said that life expectancy at birth for average
Ugandan had dropped from 45.7 years for males and 50.5 for
females in 1991 to 42.2 and 44.3 years in 1996 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the drop to precarious standards of
living in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Pays Special Attention to Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Every morning, Feng Xiren, a
71-year-old man in Shanghai, exercises in a park near his home.
</P>
<P>
"I'm leading a colorful life now that more and more special
places for entertainment for the elderly have been set up in
Shanghai," Feng said.
</P>
<P>
After exercises, he goes to the community library to read
newspapers, or sipping tea while chatting with his friends at the
local tea house. In the evening he practises calligraphy at a
nearby university for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the leading aging city in China, reports that 16.7
percent of its population is over age 60, compared to 10.2 percent
in 1979. Every three families in Shanghai has a senior citizen,
and about a quarter of all families in the city consist of elderly
people only.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Shanghai Statistics Bureau show that out of
all families with senior citizens, about 14.4 percent are made up
of a couple over age 60, and about 10 percent consist of a single
senior.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the elderly in Shanghai live with their
children and more than 20 percent of all families have three or
more generations living together.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say the family support for the elderly is
weakening and more and more elderly now live apart from their
children.
</P>
<P>
The graying of the population in Shanghai calls for urgent
changes in all social aspects that affect the elderly, such as the
social-medical insurance system, nursing services and housing
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government of Shanghai has paid great attention
to the elderly's material and cultural life. Statistics show 17
social welfare houses and 333 nursing homes have been set up in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Every day advertisements on welfare for the elderly are shown
on prime time TV, and a number of medical service stations have
been set up for the convenience of elderly people.
</P>
<P>
The service trade in Shanghai provides free, priority or
home delivery services for all senior citizens over age 70. And
elderly people without family receive regular visits and gifts at
holidays from various local enterprises or government organs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Increases Exchanges with Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan is the largest trade
partner and second largest investing country in Liaoning Province,
a major industrial base in northeast China, according to the
Liaoning Provincial Institute of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has witnessed constantly expanding exchanges and
cooperation with Japan since China opened to the outside world in
the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders from Liaoning have visited Japan on numerous
occassions, and the province has hosted visits by a number of
high-ranking Japanese leaders, including Yasuhiro Nakasone, Noboru
Takeshita and Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Exchanges between cities from the two sides have developed
rapidly, with the establishment of 17 sister city relationships.
</P>
<P>
Friendly exchanges between the two sides have greatly promoted
cooperation in the science and technology, economic and trade
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the four billion US dollar trade volume
between the two sides accounted for 36 percent of Liaoning's total
trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Japan had invested over four billion US dollars in 2,423
enterprises in Liaoning by the end of June this year, with
Liaoning ranking as one of the nation's leading provinces in terms
Japanese investments.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has used Japanese loans of 410 million US dollars
since 1986 to construct 56 projects. Japan-loaned Guanyinge
Reservoir, in the central Liaoning city of Benxi, played an
important role in flood control in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Japanese Medical Education Center at Shenyang-based
Chinese University of Medicine was established with a Japanese
grant of one billion Yen (8.3 million US dollars). The center is
currently the only medical education project of cooperation
between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
