<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Benefits from WB-Funded Water Supply Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A sip of running water from
the new tap in her house made 63-year-old Wang Erren cry.
</P>
<P>
Her tears came as she remembered her life 30 years before, as a
new bride in her small village in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, when villagers commonly contracted various
serious illnesses from drinking well water contaminated with
arsenic.
</P>
<P>
But now, more than 1,000 villages in nine disease-prone
counties have launched clean water projects, built sanitary
toilets and are promoting health education using World Bank
funding.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has granted a 10 million US dollar loan to
support the water and environmental health projects, which will
cost a total of 210 million yuan (25.3 million US dollars). The
work began in 1992, and will end next year.
</P>
<P>
About 220,000 rural families, or 930,000 people in the region
have benefited from the clean water projects, said Guo Yigang, an
official with the region's Health Department.
</P>
<P>
"Many farmers call it `the project which drives the God of
Disease away'," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Guo cautioned that the project has a long way to go, as
more than 4.3 million people in the region still drink well water
which has high levels of fluorine and arsenic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Funding for Liaoning Gains Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The use of overseas
investment in northeast China's Liaoning Province hit a record
high in the first half of the year despite the slower
rise in China's overall level.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1997, Liaoning's actual use of overseas
funding amounted to 1.2 billion US dollars, a year-on-year
increase of 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that apart from the increase in
investment, Liaoning is witnessing a more diversified use of
overseas funding.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the successful listing of B-shares of the Dalian
Wafangdian Bearing Co., Ltd. and the Benxi Iron and Steel Group
raised 172 million US dollars. The leasing contract of three
airplanes between the China Northern Airlines and Russian partners
brought in 175 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have full confidence in the returns of their
investment, which is reflected in the injection of 230 million
US dollars in funds in Dalian alone, a port city in Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
Funding was also brought in to the agricultural sector from
overseas. In the first half of the year, 20 agricultural or
agriculture-related projects were approved by the provincial
government, with total contractual overseas funding of 46.3
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that infrastructure projects, in spite of the
need of large amounts of financing, a lengthy construction period
and slow return of investment, have become a focus for overseas
investors. The 350 million US dollars of contractual investment in
this area accounted for 17 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Economists here are confident in the prospects of Liaoning's
use of overseas funds, and consider that the improving performance
of large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises will help draw
more attention from overseas entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
