<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China City Builds Moat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The north China city of
Shijiazhuang recently started construction on a city moat to ease
its water shortage and compensate for the local dry climate.
</P>
<P>
With a population of more than 1.4 million people, the city
proper covers an area of 100 square kilometers. The area has few
lakes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
The city government plans to dig five 20 m wide waterways with a
total length of 56.9 kilometers to bring in 30.58 million cubic
meters of water from a neighboring reservoir to the city each year.
</P>
<P>
The five waterways will be linked with the Shijiazhuang-Tianjin
Irrigation Canal to form a city moat, over which 22 bridges are to
be built. And green belts of 1.5 million sq m of trees and grass
will be planted along both sides of the moat.
</P>
<P>
City sources said a total of 640 million yuan will be used
to fund the two-year project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
