<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infant Mortality Declines in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Infant mortality in Bangladesh
is declining, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the child death rate per
thousand live births has come down to 110 from 262 in l960, The
New Nation said.
</P>
<P>
This progress should not generate too much of satisfaction, the
newspaper warned, quoted experts as saying "to reduce the gap by
the year 2000, the under-five mortality rate should be reduced by
8.2 percent annually."
</P>
<P>
Six percent of the world's under-five child deaths occur in
Bangladesh, the newspaper stated. Nearly 870,000 children die
every year and 2,400 a day and 100 every hour.
</P>
<P>
The main diseases causing the death of under-five children are
diarrhoetic diseases, pneumonia and malnutrition, the newspaper
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Besides most of the infants are born at home, and what is more
alarming is that more than 90 percent of the births are delivered
by untrained midwives and elderly women, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that nearly 65 percent of the deaths
could be prevented by relatively simple, inexpensive, effective
and low-cost methods, and the intervention cost to save a child is
only 350 taka (about 7.8 U.S. dollars), the newspaper added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
