<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trading Partners Question India's Export Incentives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- India's major trading
partners, the European Union (EU) and the United States, have
questioned India's various schemes offered to Indian exporters, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The EU has already challenged the incentives under the
anti-subsidy agreement of General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs
(GATT) and the U.S. has also raised the issue informally.
</P>
<P>
India's export incentives include the duty entitlement passbook
scheme (DEPB), duty drawback, special import licenses and
exemption of export profits.
</P>
<P>
India's major trading partners alleged that the export
incentives provided by the Indian government are inconsistent with
World Trade Organization (WTO) norms and are hidden subsidies.
These schemes allow "excessive" credit than the incidence of duty.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to come out with some measures and
explanations to the major trading partners, the same source said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
