<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Southern Command in Panama Goes Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The United State's
Southern Command in Panama today moved from here to Miami,
Florida, ending its 34-year residence in this Central American
country.
</P>
<P>
General Charles William, who was appointed the commander of the
military headquarters Wednesday morning, announced the movement
plan at a brief departure ceremony during which time the American
flag was lowered.
</P>
<P>
More than 770 military and nonmilitary people, the last batch
of the headquarters' personnel, will depart for Miami today.
</P>
<P>
The command, whose headquarters is based in the Quarry Heights
neighborhood, oversees military operations in Central and South
America. Recently, it has also been asked to participate in
anti-drug operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the 1977 Panama Canal Treaty between the two
governments, the U.S. is scheduled to end its military presence in
Panama by December 31, 1999, and turn the canal and all its
military bases over to the administration of the Panamanian
government.
</P>
<P>
According to the movement's timetable, the U.S. will withdraw
its command in September and reduce the number of soldiers
stationed there to 5,650 by the end of 1997. Since 1994, there
have been approximately 10,500 troops stationed in the area.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters, occupying an area of 31 hectares, comprises
209 buildings and is valued at a cost of 9.2 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
