<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Needs Concrete Action by Developed Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Search of the way
toward solving conflicts and appeal for more development
assistance dominated today's U.N. Security Council Ministerial
meeting on Africa.
</P>
<P>
Council members from Africa and other developing countries
called on their developed partners to take concrete action in
providing development assistance.
</P>
<P>
African delegates maintain that the responsibility of resolving
the conflicts should mainly rest on African countries, with the
Organization for African Unity (OAU) playing a major role.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka said
that the cooperation between the United Nations and the OAU should
be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The meeting requested that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
submit his recommendations by February 1998 on the resolution of
conflicts and reconstruction afterwards in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the initiatives by the United States, Britain and
France for their increasing participation in Africa's
peace-keeping, African delegates emphasized that international
participation should be based on the principles of the U.N.
Charter.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who is also OAU Chairman,
said: "Africans wanted their partners to become committed to a new
partnership based on sovereignty, equality and mutual benefit."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said the primary
responsibility to maintain peace and security is that of the
international community represented by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo Chong Ha called for a stop of
arms flow to the conflict areas.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first of its kind, recognized the fact that
Africa is still plagued by poverty despite progress made in recent
years. Africa's debts are increasing while external investment
decreasing.
</P>
<P>
Africa, forecast to be the only continent with growing poverty
in the next ten years, is far behind the rest of the world in
terms of development.
</P>
<P>
"Our need for new initiatives towards Africa is far less than
our need for the creation of mechanisms to implement and
coordinate the existing initiatives," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegates from countries outside Africa showed
their interest in attaching more importance to the continent.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama told the meeting that
his country has proposed at the European Union a Europe-Africa
summit to establish the first political dialogue between the two
continents and place Africa at the top of Europe's international
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Foreign Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen said her government
was preparing a new policy for Africa to increase "substantially"
its aid budget in the next 3 years.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced that she
will tour Africa before the end of the year "to make real
America's commitment to stand."
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Obuchi Keizo called for international
cooperation to hold the second Tokyo International Conference of
African Development in autumn 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are signs that major developed nations are not ready to
make real contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
