<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Idle Chilean Youth Reaches 9.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- About 9.5 percent of the
young people in Chile neither work nor study, the government said
today.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of Planning and Cooperation Antonio Lara called
the situation "worrying," since the rate applies at a national and
regional level.
</P>
<P>
A National Socio-Economic Characterization (Casen) poll,
released by the Chilean government, showed that 40.1 percent of
youth worked, 33.5 percent studied, 14.25 percent did domestic
work, and 2.65 percent either studied or worked in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, more than 340,000 young people neither worked nor
studied.
</P>
<P>
There is a distinctive difference between men and women. 52.4
percent of men have found jobs while only 27.6 percent women were
employed.
</P>
<P>
Among Chile's 3.655 million young population, those aged
between 15 and 29 accounted for 25.7 percent of the total
population in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
