<HEADLINE> Chemical Sector Expands Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China's chemical sector's
foreign trade volume is expected to hit 40 billion US dollars in
2000, with exports to account for half the total, according to
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The industry's average annual growth was 20 percent in
1991-1996 and its total volume of export, 46.1 billion US
dollars. The total trade transactions, including imports and
exports, reached 110.4 billion US dollars in the same period.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,800 foreign chemical enterprises, including 20
international chemical giants, have set up in China, bringing in
investments worth 5.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
And the Ministry of Chemical Industry (MCI) has set the goal of
soliciting foreign investment worth 12 billion US dollars by the
year 2000, doubling the current figure.
</P>
<P>
Also, MCI has signed all-round co-operation contracts with 13
global chemical companies, including Dupont of the United States,
Hoechst and Bayer of Germany and Rhone-Poulenc of France.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 300 chemical enterprises have gained the right to
engage in foreign trade on their own. About 80 firms have the
ability to earn foreign exchange exceeding ten million US dollars
a year, a dramatic rise from the 30 firms eligible in 1991. And
27 chemical producers each reported sales above 120 million US
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the industry is striving to enhance its
competitiveness by forming 55 conglomerates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
