<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Says Haze an International Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The widespread fires plaguing
Indonesia and the choking smoke blanketing neighboring countries
have turned into an "international catastrophe," the head of the
World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) said.
</P>
<P>
The scale of the forest fires "is so big that they not only
affect Indonesia, but other countries like Malaysia and
Singapore," WWF Head Shed Babar Ali said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, in addition to Malaysia and
Singapore, the fires have blanketed Brunei, the Philippines and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Ali, who arrived here on Wednesday for a five-day visit, made
the remarks after meeting with Indonesian Forestry Minister
Djamaludin Suryohadikusumo, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Ali's remarks coincided with Thursday's presidential statement
that the forest fires and the smoke, better known as the "haze,"
are a national disaster.
</P>
<P>
Ali called on the Indonesian government to totally ban the
slash-and-burn method for clearing land and plantation areas in a
bid to prevent further forest fires.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto recently issued a national ban on
slash-and-burn land clearing methods. Following this, official
warnings have been issued to 176 companies who have allegedly
continued such practices.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare Azwar Anas said
Thursday that more than 80,000 hectares of forest areas had been
destroyed by fires since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, State Minister for Environment Sarwono Kusumaamadja
said that at least 300,000 hectares of forest had been burned.
</P>
<P>
However, sources with access to satellite photos said Thursday
that between 600,000 and 800,000 hectares of forest and plantation
had been hit by fires.
</P>
<P>
The haze has put 20 million people in danger of respiratory
problems in the country as well as in neighboring countries. It
has left at least two people dead from respiratory infections in
Indonesia, officials here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
