<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparations Start for HK Legislative Council Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The election procedure of the
first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region will soon begin, today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Legislative Council is expected to pass the
Legislative Council Ordinance this Saturday, which will lay down
rules for the election.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Constitutional Affairs Michael Suen said at a
luncheon yesterday that an independent Electoral Affairs
Commission will be established, which will present plans on
geographical constituency demarcation, voter registration and
election procedures to the chief executive before the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that the government will begin to register voters at
the end of this year and the beginning of next year. It is
estimated that about two million families will be involved as the
government is determined to encourage all eligible permanent
residents to vote.
</P>
<P>
An 800-strong election committee, which will produce 10 members
of the 60-member Legislative Council, will be set up at the end
of April. The formal election will begin at the end to May.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, 20 legislators will come out of the
direct voting and the other 30 from functional constituencies.
</P>
<P>
"This election will be open, fair, honest and acceptable to the
public," Suen said.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the election will not be a setback to democracy
as some people hold.
</P>
<P>
To clarify major controversies, Suen said that the proportional
representation mechanism was designed to include small political
parties in the process. Under the traditional "one person one
vote" method used in direct elections, smaller parties are often
squeezed out of the process.
</P>
<P>
Proportional representation can allow the different opinions of
voters to be reflected in the distribution of the legislative
seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
