<HEADLINE> Two Vessels Sink Outside Colombo Harbor in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A foreign vessel chartered to
transport daily necessities to the Jaffna Peninsula and a local
tugboat sank off Colombo Port on Wednesday night due to stormy
weather, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 25 crew members on board the ship "Astoria," a
German built vessel owned by the Astoria Shipping Company in St.
Vincent, and the local tugboat "Nigiri" were brought ashore safely
by rescuers who risked the choppy seas and gale winds to carry out
the operation.
</P>
<P>
The "Astoria" had been loaded with rice, cement and other
provisions and had been anchoring outside the harbor when raging
seas and gale winds sank it within a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
It had planned to transport those goods to the Jaffna Peninsula
in the north of Sri Lanka, port officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The two boats were valued at more than 1.5 million U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
