<HEADLINE> Drought-Related Deaths Rise in Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of drought-related
deaths in Indonesia's Irian Jaya province rose to 271 Thursday as
haze continued to hinder relief operations to the
disaster-stricken area, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Social Services Inten Soeweno said last night that
253 people had died in the Jayawijaya Regency, 11 in the Merauke
Regency and seven from the Puncak Jaya Regency.
</P>
<P>
A total of 73 people were being treated by doctors in Merauke,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were caused by cholera and other
drought-induce diseases and food shortage in the areas.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought, which began three months ago, has also
triggered forest fires in the province. The fires have razed
130,135 hectares of forest, a local forestry service official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Inten said the government had sent food, medical supplies and
other relief to the areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
