<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse to Relax Trading Limits in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of
Thailand (SET) will begin to enforce new rules in December this
year to allow share prices on the market to float within a wider
range, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, the price rise for a share on a single
trading day will be allowed up to 30 percent of the share price,
while the price fall will be allowed by 27 percent on a single
trading day.
</P>
<P>
The Thai bourse currently only allows a share price to rise or
fall within the limit of 10 percent on a trading day.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, the trading on the bourse will be
suspended for a period of time if the SET index falls too far.
</P>
<P>
The trading on the bourse will be suspended for 30 minutes if
the whole index drops 50 points on a trading day and the trading
will be suspended for one hour if the index drops 100 points.
</P>
<P>
The trading will be stopped for the rest of the session once it
falls more than 200 points on a single trading day.
</P>
<P>
The new rules are planned as an increasing number of local
listed firms suffer big losses due to the floatation of the baht
and face the threat to be delisted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Thai bourse will begin to enforce new rules of
credit balance and short-selling on January 2 next year, which
will show the green light for short-selling.
</P>
<P>
The Thai bourse currently bans short-selling by borrowing
shares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
