<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian PM Says International Court's Ruling Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister
Horn Gyula said today that a ruling by the International Court of
Justice on the Hungarian-Slovak dispute over the construction of a
hydropower station on the Danube River was fair, and Hungary
should abide by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Horn made the remarks this evening on a TV news program.
</P>
<P>
As early as 1950, Hungary and the then Czechoslovakia proposed
the two countries jointly build a hydropower stations on the
Danube, their boundary river.
</P>
<P>
In 1977, they signed an accord to cooperate on the construction
of two hydropower stations on the Danube, but the construction did
not begin until the early 1980's due to a shortage of funds.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, thousands of Hungarians staged demonstrations. They
demanded the cancellation of the accord on the grounds of
protecting the environment. Consequently, the Hungarian government
withdrew from the construction in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Czechoslovakia however modified the original design scheme in
1991 and proceeded with the construction. In 1992, Hungary
unilaterally declared the abrogation of the accord they had signed
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Czechoslovakia eventually disintegrated into two nations in
January 1993: the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic. The
Slovak Republic continued with the construction of the hydropower
station, and now the station has begun generating electricity.
</P>
<P>
However, the hydropower station reportedly inflicted many
harmful effects upon Hungary's environment. So Hungary demanded
compensation from the Slovak Republic, but its demands were turned
down.
</P>
<P>
In April 1993, Hungary submitted the dispute to the
International Court of Justice in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
The court, after four years of investigation, ruled today that
Hungary's acts in unilaterally abrogating their accord was
illegal, and so was the Slovak Republic's in modifying the
original design.
</P>
<P>
The two countries were instructed to compensate each other for
losses due to their respective faults.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian government discussed the court's ruling today and
announced that it would elaborate its stand on the ruling to the
Congress on September 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
