<HEADLINE> Thai Ex-PM Wins Defamation Court Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Thai former prime minister
Banharn Silpa-archa has won a court case in which he was accused
of taking bribes from a Swedish shipbuilder, according to a
Bangkok Post report today.
</P>
<P>
On November 28, 1995, the Siam Post newspaper carried a
front-page report saying Banharn had taken bribes from Kockums, a
Swedish shipbuilder.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Banharn took the money before the July 2,
1995 general election. Kockums was said to be offering financial
support for Banharn's Chart Thai Party in the election to boost
its own chances of winning a contract to sell two medium-sized
submarines to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The court found that the accusation was without evidence and
was a serious libel.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Aroon Larnlue, the former editor of Siam Post, was
given a one-year suspended jail term and fined 100,000 baht (2,700
US dollars) for defaming the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Siam Post Co. and Post Publishing PLC, the second and third
defendants in the criminal court case, were also fined 100,000
baht each. The report did not say when the sentences were handed
down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
