<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Value of Peru's Aquatic Products Up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The export value of Peru's
aquatic products industry during the first eight months of this
year increased 37 percent to 1.03 billion U.S. dollars, Fishing
Minister Ludwig Meier Cornejo said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister also predicted 1.3 billion dollars in exports for
the entire year, which would entail an increase of more than 22
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the January-August export figure of 1.03 billion dollars,
the traditional products, which include fish meal and fish oil,
produced 909 million dollars, while non-traditional products
amounted to 121 million dollars, Meier said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that non-traditional products, referring to
those for direct human consumption, will continue to increase in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed a recovery in the fishing products industry for
direct human consumption, especially an increase in the production
of canned and frozen fish products, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that his ministry would adopt all necessary
measures to help promote the production and export of
non-traditional products.
</P>
<P>
Peru is one of the major aquatic product suppliers in the
world. The country's production of fishing products reached 9.6
million tons in 1996, up 8.9 percent over the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
