<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Inflation to Be Less Than That of U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is expected to
see an inflation rate as low as, if not lower than, that of the
United States this year, the Finance Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund predicts that the price index
of consumer goods in the United States could be 2.4 percent, or
1.2 percent in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil reported in August a 0.75 percent drop in the price
index of consumer goods, and the Statistics Institute specialists
foresee the same trend for the coming months.
</P>
<P>
After the "hyper-inflation" of up to 5,135.5 percent in June of
1994, and the 66.2 percent in April 1990, Brazil's inflation fell
sharply to 14.78 percent in 1995 and 9.34 percent in 1996,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the past 12 months, the country's inflation dropped further
to 4.65 percent, according to the Brazilian Institute of Geography
and Statistics. 
</P>
