<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA President in Favour of World Club Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- UEFA president Lennart
Johansson said on Thursday he was in favour of a world club
championship.
</P>
<P>
Although many delegates at UEFA's presidents and general
secretaries conference refused to commit themselves to the idea,
Johansson said: "When it was discussed at FIFA, I supported it, so
for me there was never a question about if it would happen, only
when.
</P>
<P>
"You will have one champion from each of the six
Confederations, plus the champions of the host country and
possibly the reigning champions, it depends," said Johansson
later.
</P>
<P>
But not every delegate was in support.
</P>
<P>
Various proposals have been put forward for the compeitition,
which would effectively replace the annual match played in Tokyo
between the European and South American champions.
</P>
<P>
That match, which has been known as the Toyota Cup since it was
relaunched with a sponsorship deal by Toyota in 1980, is
contrcated to continue in its current format until 2002.
</P>
<P>
No decision was taken by the conference although member
federations were asked to report their views back to UEFA's
executive committee within the next month.
</P>
<P>
The executive committee are then likely to decide how to
proceed at their next meeting in Geneva on December 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
