<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governments Urged to Adopt New Norms on Water Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The 21st conference of the
International Water Supply Association (IWSA) concluded here today
after issuing a call on governments worldwide to take common
action and formulate new norms on water use.
</P>
<P>
The four-day IWSA meeting, which opened Monday, was attended by
representatives and experts from more than 100 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Participants debated on the issues related to global water
resource and water supply in every country.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the mankind is facing an unprecedented
water supply crisis caused by the ever-increasing world
population, climate change and wide-range water pollution.
</P>
<P>
At the closing ceremony, a senior official of the conference
said that the crucial moment has come for the mankind to seriously
deal with the water supply crisis.
</P>
<P>
As long as the governments of all countries carry out a common
strategy, the mankind is able to tide over the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IWSA was founded in 1947 and it holds a conference every
two years. The next IWSA meeting will be held in Buenos Aires,
capital of Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
