<HEADLINE> Engine Maker Issues B Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China's second largest
single-cylinder diesel engine maker, Jiangsu Wuling Diesel Engine
Co. Ltd, began its issuance of 100 million foreign currency B
shares Thursday, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company expects the shares, priced at 4.31 yuan (0.51
shares) each, to raise a net 405.14 million yuan (about 48.8
million US dollars) excluding issue costs, according to the
company's prospectus.
</P>
<P>
Shenyin-Wanguo Securities was lead manager of the issuance,
while Credit Lyonnais Securities was the international
co-ordinator.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds are to be used to expand production facilities and for
technical upgrading.
</P>
<P>
Output of the firm's major product, single-cylinder diesel
engines for agricultural machinery, will be expanded to one
million units by the year 2000 from the current 600,000 units, the
prospectus said.
</P>
<P>
The company estimates 1997 post-tax profits at a minimum 110
million yuan (about 13.25 million US dollars) with net earnings at
0.495 yuan per share on a fully diluted basis, the prospectus
said.
</P>
<P>
After the issuance, B shares will account for 40 percent of the
company's total 250 million outstanding shares. The State would
own 148 million shares or 59.2 percent with the remainder owned by
domestic companies, the prospectus said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
