<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru to Fight "El Nino" Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government will
allocate more than 150 million U.S. dollars to help ease
consequences caused by the "El Nino" phenomenon across the
country, Minister to the Presidency Daniel Hokama said today.
</P>
<P>
In Peru alone, there will be an estimated 1.5 million victims
of the "El Nino" phenomenon, which produces rains, floods, and
drought, Hokama said.
</P>
<P>
He added that rains and possible floods caused by river
outflows in northern Peru would affect at least 1 million people,
while in the drought-hit zone of the Andean area, the victims
would total half a million.
</P>
<P>
The 150 million dollars allocated by the Peruvian government to
help the victims would mainly be used to re-establish and maintain
drainage systems, power transmission lines, as well as health
centers and school buildings, the presidency minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government also planned to relocate 10,500 families,
warehouse 25,000 tons of foodstuffs and clean some 2,000
kilometers of river beds and agricultural drainage canals to
prevent floods, he added.
</P>
<P>
The "El Nino" usually originates in the Pacific coast of Peru
and Ecuador, but causes disturbances in the world's climate. This
year's "El Nino" effects started from the very beginning of the
year, but experts said it would increase in December and continue
until the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 1982-1983 "El Nino" left losses worth of 8 billion dollars
in Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970926.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Joins U.N. Sea Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Chile has become a member of
the United Nations Convention on Sea Laws after completing all the
procedures required to join it, the Foreign Affairs Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
Chile was the first country to officially announce on June 23,
1947, through then President Gabriel Gonzales Videla, a maritime
declaration, which was ratified in 1952 through an agreement
between Chile, Ecuador and Peru.
</P>
<P>
This declaration, first supported by the Southern Pacific
countries, and then by developing countries, was adopted by the
United Nations Convention on Sea Laws signed in Montego Bay,
Jamaica, on December 10, 1982, in the form of an exclusive
economic zone of 200 nautical miles.
</P>
<P>
The document on Chile's adherence to the Sea Convention, which
had gone through the Chilean Parliament, was submitted on August
24 of this year to the U.N. secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Chile was admitted to the Convention on September 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
