<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A drive to study documents of the 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) has started all over the
country and local party officials are required to take effective
measures to implement the guidelines of Jiang Zemin's report
delivered at the congress.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng wound up his visit to Kazakhstan and
returned home Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday published detailed information on the import
tariff cuts announced earlier this month, according to the General
Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
The tariff cuts, to be applied from october 1, will affect 4,874
kinds of commodities and slash China's average tariff rate by 26
percent down to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage story tells of the drafting process of the 15th
National Party Congress report, titled "Holding High the Great
Banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory for an All-Round Advancement of the
Cause of Building Socialism with Chinese Characteristics."
</P>
<P>
The report was deemed the political declaration of the
Communists as they approach the new century and also the Party's
Guide to action.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji met in Beijing's Great Hall of the
People with US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin Thursday. Zhu said
Sino-US relations have maintained good momentum for development
this year, with frequent high-level exchanges and fresh progress
made in the economic, technological and cultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, meeting today with a group from Hong Kong, spoke about
training better management personnel and called for raising
management work to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Reform of the United Nations aims to strengthen the world
body and should reflect the common interests of all member states,
said Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen when addressing the 52nd
session of the UN General Assembly Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- The World Bank (WB) and International Monetary Fund (IMF)
expressed sincere appreciation to China, host country of the 52nd
WB/IMF meetings. 
