<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Sets New Rules to Protect Banks From Bad Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank
has redefined past-due or non-performing loans to protect banks
from loan defaults, local newspaper Business World reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulation, loans payable in both monthly
or quarterly installments are to be considered past due "whenever
these are in arrears for more than three months or one quarter (of
a year)", the report said.
</P>
<P>
Previously, these loans were considered past due when
installments were delayed for more than six months.
</P>
<P>
Banks were also given one year to implement the changes in the
determination of non-performing loans, it said.
</P>
<P>
While local banks have relatively low non-performing loans,
averaging about 1.5 percent compared with Thailand's 7.7 percent,
the deterioration of credit quality and the increasing number of
companies seeking debt restructuring have raised some concern.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also required banks to set up a general
loan-loss provision equivalent to 2 percent of total loan
portfolio in addition to the allowance for probable losses on
individually identified uncollectible accounts such as
sub-standard, doubtful and bad debts.
</P>
<P>
Banks operating for more than five years were given one year to
make the necessary changes in their loan-loss provisions, it said.
</P>
<P>
Those operating for less than five years were required to have
a loan-loss reserve of 1 percent of their total loan portfolio
within one year and the balance of 1 percent set up on the second
and third year in equal amounts.
</P>
<P>
Central bank deputy governor Alberto Reyes said the measures
were aimed at making the required loan ratios of banks at par with
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Philippines Bankers Association's chief economist Johnny Noe
Ravalo said the twin measures represented a "very good signal".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
