<HEADLINE> Poland to Have Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A coalition government will
administer Poland because no party won a clear majority of votes
in the parliamentary election, according to results released today.
</P>
<P>
The Solidarity Election Action (AWS), the country's largest
organization set up in June 1996 and composed of 38 rightist
parties and groups, won 33.8 percent of the vote and became the
biggest party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
It obtained 201 seats in the 460-seat house of representatives
and 51 seats in the 100-member senate.
</P>
<P>
It was immediately followed by the ruling Democratic Left
Alliance (SLD) which won 27.1 percent of the vote. SLD got 164 and
28 seats in two houses of the parliament respectively.
</P>
<P>
The AWS leaders have embarked on the formation of a coalition
government and Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, the SLD
leader, has decided to resign.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary elections take place every four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
