<HEADLINE> Chilean Soccer Players End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Players representing all
professional Chilean clubs who attended a assembly unanimously
voted to end the strike on Thursday, according to Carlos Ramos,
president of the players' union.
</P>
<P>
The clubs also agreed to lift sanctions against players who
joined the two-week strike.
</P>
<P>
The decision came just one day after Diego Maradona warned a
strike by Chilean soccer players demanding better working
conditions could spread throughout South America.
</P>
<P>
No details were available on the agreement, but Ramos indicated
the players' key demands had been accepted. But "there are some
small details that are yet to be ironed," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the first and second division tournaments will
resume normally over the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
