<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian to Standardize Accounting Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian
province plans to hold inspections to better discipline the
accounting field in the coming 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The province first launched the public accounting business in
1981. It now has 118 accounting agencies and 110 auditing
agencies, with more than 4,000 certified public accountants (CPAs)
and auditors.
</P>
<P>
Problems exit in the rapid developing business, however, and
some agencies have been found to be providing companies with false
financial statements.
</P>
<P>
"The inspection will look into whether those agencies are
operating in accordance with laws and regulations, and will see
how the provincial CPAs are doing in their business," said a
provincial official.
</P>
<P>
And, those which have repeatedly been the target of public
complaint will be the primary focus of the inspections, he added.
</P>
<P>
The province will also conduct tax reviews of accounting
agencies doing overseas businesses, as well as of overseas
accounting companies' offices in Fujian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
