<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Increase Ostrich Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China is to make ostrich meat
and other products available to ordinary people by increasing the
number of the big bird to some one million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Guo Shanling, deputy director of the Planning Department of the
China Ostrich Development Association, said the goal is not so
unreasonable because there are 80,000 of the birds now, which is
10,000 times the number in 1993 when China started raising
ostriches by using eight birds bought from the United States.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, ostriches will cost from 1,500 to 2,000 yuan (187 to
250 US dollars) each, said Guo, and ostrich products won't be seen
as luxury items that are beyond reach of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
The ostrich promoter is here for an exhibition of ostrich
products, from artwork like egg painting to things like boots,
handbags, wallets, and belts.
</P>
<P>
According to Guo, more than 20 provinces and cities in China
now have ostrich farms, but most of the ostriches are for
breeding, although some have been exported to Asian countries like
South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
"We have developed processing techniques for ostrich-related
products, but we lack the birds to build up an industry," said Guo.
</P>
<P>
Since South Africa has dominated the European and American
markets with its ostrich products, China will target East-Asia and
North Europe as potential ostrich products importers.
</P>
<P>
Because of the high cost and complex breeding technology, China
at present is not encouraging individuals to start ostrich farms,
Guo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
