<HEADLINE> Brazilian Real Devaluation Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian
currency, the real, faces a 2.8 to 3.5 percent devaluation by the
end of the year, said Jose Roberto Mendonza, Finance Ministry's
economic policies secretary, here today.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation level will depend on the performance of the
index of prices to the consumer, announced Mendonza, quoted today
by the press.
</P>
<P>
The drop of the value of the real confirms the trend of the
government's policy of guaranteeing the competitivity of Brazilian
products.
</P>
<P>
Mendonza dismissed that the devaluation in the foreseen level
could have an immediate repercussion on the balance of trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
