<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Create Two Electoral Districts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Two additional electoral
districts will be created in New Zealand in the next general
election, Statistics NZ said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the two, one will be a Maori electoral district, increasing
the electorates for Maori from five to six.
</P>
<P>
On the North Island, a new general electoral district will be
added, bringing the total number on the island to 45.
</P>
<P>
But on the South Island, the number of general electoral
districts will remain at 16.
</P>
<P>
The total seats in the Parliament will be unchanged, staying at
120. The listed seats will be reduced to 53 from 55 to cope with
the change.
</P>
<P>
The extra general electorate is almost certain in Auckland,
where population increases have been the greatest.
</P>
<P>
Government statistician Len Cook said a disproportionate number
of immigrants had settled on the North Island, and particularly in
Auckland, from 1990 to 1996, adding to pressure on electorates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
