<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Meets Panamanian Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The principle of
keeping only non-official contacts with Taiwan, which most of the
members of the United Nations adhere to, is also applicable to
Panama, said Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
here today.
</P>
<P>
China's reunification is the inevitable trend of times and it
is widely accepted by the international community, said Qian when
he met with Panamanian Foreign Minister Ricardo Alberto Arias at
the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Most of the U.N. member states handle the Taiwan question in
accordance with the relevant resolutions of the United Nations,
that is, keeping only non-official contacts with Taiwan, Qian
noted, adding that this principle is also applicable to Panama in
carrying out its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Qian also said that China has been always supportive to Panama
in its efforts to resume its exercise of sovereignty over the
Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that after its return to Panama, the
canal will continue to effectively serve the navigation for the
world.
</P>
<P>
Arias, while expressing thanks to China for its consistent
support for his country on the question, hoped that China will
participate in the development and construction of the canal in
the future.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Panamanian people and the Chinese people
have friendly relations for a long time. The oversea Chinese have
made great contributions to the construction of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian foreign minister stressed that Panama will
continue developing relations with China, enhancing bilateral
economic and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed Arias on China's two major events this year:
the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China and the
resumption of exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong. "These two
events would have a far reaching influence in the future of our
country," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund just had an
annual conference in Hong Kong, which drew economists and
financial experts from different countries. The fact itself
indicated that foreign countries have seen the prosperity of China
and Hong Kong as well, according to the Chinese vice-premier.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, he said, it is in accordance with
the interests of both China and Panama to create conditions to
develop their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Arias said his country follows the 15th National Congress of
the Chinese Communist Party in China and Hong Kong's return to the
motherland with great enthusiasm. The convention of the World Bank
conference in Hong Kong showed that the international community is
full of confidence in the future of China and Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
