<HEADLINE> 5 Permanent Members Urge All Parties in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain, China,
France, Russia and the United States, the permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council, today called on all parties in the Middle
East to implement in full commitments made under existing
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The five nations also urged them to refrain from actions that
preempt the upcoming negotiations and worsen both the political
and the economic situation in the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The five nations indicated their positions in a statement
issued after a meeting between their foreign ministers and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed deep concern at the current
difficulties in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
It also condemned vigorously acts of terrorism and violence
aimed at destroying the peace process and expressed their deep
outrage at the terrorist attacks in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The five states supported the continuing efforts of the
co-sponsors of the peace process and also of the European Union
and urged all parties to resume without delay negotiations in the
framework of this process and on the basis of the agreements
already reached and in accordance with U.N. Security Council
resolution 242 and 338 and with the principle of "land for peace."
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed their hope that the negotiations
between Israel, Syria and Lebanon could resume soon on a mutually
agreed basis and in accordance with relevant Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They urged all interested parties to avoid an escalation of
violence and tension in southern Lebanon and cooperate within the
monitoring group, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
